{In the previous article, we have focused on Black advancing his queenside
majority. When adopting this plan he frequently relies on the fact that he can
keep White's majority under control by defending the e5-square against the
central break e4-e5. The g7-bishop plays an important part, of course. Another
aspect is that after e4-e5 the d5-pawn is likely to become vulnerable. On the
other hand, if properly sustained by pieces, this pawn could become a
threatening force. We will distinguish between two main situations: White
breaks the center with the help of his pieces or by using the f-pawn to
sustain his colleague. We shall start with the optimal situation for White
corresponding to the first category when the attack on the wing is effectively
met by a central break by perfect piece coordination.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5
d6 4. Nc3 g6 5. Nf3 Bg7 6. g3 O-O 7. Bg2 e6 8. O-O exd5 9. cxd5 Na6 10. h3 {[#]
} Nc7 $6 ({Now and on the next move Black does not pay attention to the
advance of the e-pawn.} 10... Re8 {is an important alternative.}) 11. e4 b5 $6
{Played in the same careless style.} ({True it was late for using the rook for
delaying the pawn advance:} 11... Re8 $6 12. Re1 Nd7 13. Bf4 Qe7 14. e5 $16 {
with advantage to White since ...dxe5 now or within a couple of moves would
run into d5-d6.}) ({The best chance to stay in the game was} 11... Nd7 12. Bf4
Qe7 $14 {with freer play for White but a solid position for Black.}) {[#]} 12.
e5 $1 {With the actual piece placement the d5-pawn is more of a strength than
weakness so there is no counter-indication to the thematic last move.} Nfe8 ({
Trying to keep the d-pawn. If} 12... dxe5 13. d6 Ne6 14. Nxe5 $16 {White does
not even have to take the exchange, thus offering Black some chances on light
squares, as his position is very strong anyway.}) 13. Bg5 $1 {An active
developing move causing Black problems with finding a good square for the
queen.} f6 ({This weakens the e6-square and obstructs the own bishop but} 13...
Qd7 {puts the queen in a dangerous situation:} 14. Ne4 dxe5 ({Or if} 14... c4
15. exd6 Nxd6 16. Nc5 {Black cannot defend e7 with 16...Qe8 due to 17.Re1
trapping the queen while} Qf5 17. Be7 {wins the exchange.}) 15. Nxc5 Qd6 ({
The queen is a bad blocker but there is no way of keeping this square for the
knight.} 15... Qxd5 16. Be7 {does not offer enough compensation for the
exchange as White remains active.}) 16. Rc1 $16 {With strong white pressure.})
14. exd6 Nxd6 ({Otherwise} 14... fxg5 15. dxc7 Nxc7 {Keeping g5-defended but
unblocking d5.} 16. d6 Ne6 17. Re1 $16 {with strong white initiative. The game
move keeps the control on d6, even though not for long.}) {[#]} 15. Be3 {
This and the next move show that Black's queenside action has only left him
with weaknesses.} Na6 (15... c4 {allows} 16. Nd4 $16 {followed by Nc6 soon.
This is one of the situations when the white light-squared bishop is optimally
placed in the fianchetto by over defending d5 and increasing the control over
c6.}) 16. a4 $1 b4 17. Nb5 {The first step to unblocking the passed pawn.} Bb7
18. Nxd6 Qxd6 19. Nd2 $1 {Once again White can regroup with all the comfort
mainly due to his bishop.} Rfd8 ({Only not} 19... Bxd5 $2 20. Nc4 $18 {wins a
piece.}) 20. Nc4 Qd7 {[#]White has removed the blockade on d6 and has a
strategically winning position. In the next phase he will slowly regroup,
putting his main bid on the central pawn.} 21. Qb3 Qf7 22. Rad1 Rac8 23. Rd2
Bf8 24. Rfd1 Rd7 25. Na5 {With the major pieces optimally placed White starts
improving the position of his minor ones.} Ba8 26. Bf1 Nb8 27. Bb5 Rdd8 28. Bc4
Bd6 29. Nc6 Rd7 30. Nxb8 Rxb8 31. Bxc5 $1 {White won a pawn and after twenty
more moves the game.} Kg7 32. Bxd6 Rxd6 33. Qe3 Re8 34. Qc5 Red8 35. Qxb4 Qd7
36. Kh2 Qf5 37. Qc5 a6 38. Qe3 h5 39. b3 Bxd5 40. Qf4 Bxc4 41. Qxf5 Rxd2 42.
Rxd2 gxf5 43. Rxd8 Bxb3 44. a5 f4 45. gxf4 Kg6 46. Kg3 Bc4 47. Kh4 Bb5 48. Rd6
Bc4 49. f5+ Kxf5 50. Kxh5 Ke5 51. Rb6 Be2+ 52. Kg6 1-0

