{With the bishop placed elsewhere than on g2, the central break tends to lead
to double-edged consequences as the d5-pawn remains more vulnerable while the
intrusion to c6 is less probable. The next game was by far less one-sided than
I thought after I signed the scoresheet below zero.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5
d6 4. Nc3 g6 5. e4 Bg7 6. h3 O-O 7. Bg5 e6 8. Bd3 exd5 9. cxd5 Re8 10. Nf3 c4
11. Bc2 b5 12. a3 Na6 13. O-O Nc5 14. Re1 Qb6 15. Qd2 a5 {[#]Black's
counterplay starts taking concrete forms so White has little choice:} 16. e5 $1
dxe5 17. Nxe5 Bf5 $5 ({An interesting dynamic approach. The static} 17... Bb7
18. Rad1 {is also unclear, as the c6-square is well defended and White's only
constructive plan is advancing his central pawn, with uncertain consequences.})
18. Bxf5 $5 ({Embarking interesting play. If} 18. d6 Bd3 {Black exchanges his
c4-pawn for the d6-pawn with equality.}) 18... Nb3 19. Qf4 {[#]} Nxa1 $2 {
In the most interesting moment Black overlooks the next move.} (19... Nh5 $1 {
would have kept the game unclear. Many of White's pieces are hanging so he has
to resort to extreme measures to avoid losing material:} 20. Nd7 $1 Nxa1 $1 ({
But not} 20... Nxf4 $2 21. Nxb6 Nxa1 22. Rxa1 $18) 21. Rxa1 ({The move order
is forced for White. too for if} 21. Nxb6 $2 Rxe1+ 22. Kh2 Nxf4 $19) 21... Qb7
22. Qf3 gxf5 23. Qxf5 Ra7 24. Nc5 Qb6 {with excellent white compensation for
the exchange but not more.}) 20. Be6 $1 {A thunder out of the blue. White cuts
off the connection of the enemy queen with the kingside, thus obtaining a
winning attack.} fxe6 21. Bxf6 exd5 ({The lesser evil was probably} 21... Rf8
22. Nd7 Qd8 $5 23. Nxf8 Qxf6 24. Qxf6 Bxf6 25. Nxe6 $16 {with "just" a clearly
better ending.}) ({Knaak recommends} 21... Bxf6 22. Nd7 $1 Bxc3 {overlooking
that after} 23. Nxb6 Bxe1 24. Nxa8 Rxa8 25. Qe4 Bd2 26. dxe6 $18 {White wins
due to the uncoordinated and hanging black pieces.}) 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. Qf7+ Kh8
24. Nxd5 {[#]The knights are impressive.} Qe6 (24... Qd6 {is no better:} 25.
Nf6 Re7 26. Nxg6+ hxg6 27. Qxe7 $18) 25. Qxe6 ({A clearer win was} 25. Nf6 $1
Qxf7 26. Nxf7+ Kg7 27. Nxe8+ Rxe8 28. Rxe8 Kxf7 29. Rb8 $18) 25... Rxe6 26.
Nf7+ Kg7 27. Rxe6 Kxf7 28. Re7+ Kg8 29. Rb7 $18 {and White did not face any
serious problems converting his obvious advantage into a win.} Nb3 30. Rxb5 Rd8
31. Ne3 Nd2 32. f3 Rd3 33. Kf2 a4 34. Rd5 c3 35. bxc3 Rxd5 36. Nxd5 Nc4 37. Ke2
Kf7 38. Kd3 Nb2+ 39. Kd4 1-0

