{The second way of carrying out e4-e5 implies using the f-pawn for sustaining
his colleague. We will not examine here the cases when ...dxe5 can be simply
met with fxe5, with a crushing space advantage, but the more interesting case
when White carries out what we could call the Penrose plan.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nc3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 g6 6. e4 d6 7. Bd3 Bg7 8. Nge2 O-O 9. O-O a6 10.
a4 Qc7 11. h3 Nbd7 12. f4 Re8 13. Ng3 c4 14. Bc2 Nc5 15. Qf3 {[#]White does
not make a secret out of his plan of preparing e4-e5. Tal's antidote will
prove ineffective.} Nfd7 $6 {After this move none less than 4 black pieces are,
directly or not, control the e5-square. But this does not prevent e4-e5
physically and what's worse weakens the control over e4 and breaks the queen's
connection with the kingside.} ({The correct continuation is} 15... Rb8 16. Be3
(16. e5 {is premature as after} dxe5 {17.f5 Black has 17...e4 with strong
counterplay while after} 17. fxe5 Rxe5 18. Bf4 Nfd7 {he gets more than enough
compensation for the exchange.}) 16... b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. e5 dxe5 19. fxe5
Rxe5 20. Bd4 Rg5 {with adequate counterplay.}) 16. Be3 b5 17. axb5 Rb8 18. Qf2
axb5 {[#]} 19. e5 $1 {Quite a nice way to play against one of the most
brilliant World champions.} dxe5 $2 {The threats exd6 followed by Nce4 or Nce4
at once are unpleasant but the last move just plays into White's hands.} 20. f5
$1 {The essence of the "Penrose attack". White gets strong kingside threats
and the e4-square for his knights.} ({Tal might have expected} 20. fxe5 Rf8 {
with white initiative but certain black counter chances due to the weakness of
the e5-pawn.}) 20... Bb7 ({Due to the threat fxg6 followed by Qf7+ Black has
no time for the aforementioned counter-break ...e5-e4. And if} 20... Rf8 $2 21.
f6 $1 Bh8 22. d6 $1 Qxd6 23. Nf5 $1 Qxf6 24. Nd5 {White's attack is winning.})
{[#]} 21. Rad1 ({A strong consolidating move, but} 21. fxg6 fxg6 22. Bxg6 $1 {
would have been even straighter, for instance} hxg6 23. Qf7+ Kh7 (23... Kh8 24.
Qxg6 $18) 24. Nh5 Rg8 25. Nf6+ Kh8 26. Rf5 $18 {In order to avoid mate Black
needs giving up his queen with} Nxf6) 21... Ba8 22. Nce4 {White's initiative
is hard to control already.} Na4 23. Bxa4 bxa4 24. fxg6 fxg6 25. Qf7+ Kh8 26.
Nc5 1-0

