{Many years ago it was my trainer Theodor Ghitescu who made me familiar with
the Penrose plan, one of his specialties and favorite methods, but recently I
discovered that he was not always successful with it. In the next game the
aforementioned ...e5-e4 turned tables around, yielding Black the initiative.} 
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 d6 4. Nc3 g6 5. e4 Bg7 6. Bd3 e6 7. Nge2 exd5 8. cxd5
O-O 9. O-O Na6 10. a3 Re8 11. f3 Nd7 12. f4 Nf6 13. h3 c4 14. Bc2 Nc5 15. Ng3
Nfd7 16. e5 dxe5 17. f5 {[#]With respect to the previous game, White is a few
tempi down from the point of view of his global attack. He would need at least
his queen on f2 to make things work out properly.} e4 $1 {In the absence of
pressure along the f-file Black is in time clearing the path for his bishop
and rook, avoiding the suffocating blockade on e4 at the same time. All other
continuations offer White at least good compensation for the pawn. For
instance:} (17... Nf6 18. Be3 Qd6 19. fxg6 hxg6 20. Qf3 $44 {and White has
caught up with the development stage from the Penrose-Tal game.}) (17... Qb6
18. Be3 Qxb2 19. Nge4 Nxe4 20. Nxe4 $44 {is very dangerous for Black due to
the misplaced queen and already vulnerable king.}) (17... b5 {wastes a tempo
which White can use with} 18. Be3 e4 19. Bd4 $44) 18. Ncxe4 (18. Be3 Qh4 $17 {
possibly followed by ...Nd3 is not a solution either.}) 18... Nxe4 19. Nxe4 Ne5
{[#]Black has activated his play and White's incomplete development makes him
vulnerable.} 20. f6 $6 {Stabilizing the queenside is an obvious concession as
it does not offer attacking chances.} ({True,} 20. g4 {is too slow:} b5 21. Bg5
Qb6+ 22. Kh2 Bb7 23. fxg6 hxg6 $15 {and the White king does not feel too
comfortable. One point is that the tempting} 24. Nf6+ $2 {runs into} Bxf6 25.
Rxf6 Qc7 26. Kg1 Nd3 $19 {ith decisive counterplay.}) ({Possibly best was} 20.
Nc3 {stabilizing the centre, but Black's position would have remained
preferable fter} Qb6+ 21. Kh1 Bxf5 22. Bxf5 gxf5 23. Qh5 (23. Rxf5 Nd3 $19 {
offers Black a crushing domination.}) 23... Qg6 24. Qxf5 Nd3 25. Bd2 Rad8 $15)
20... Bf8 21. Be3 ({If} 21. Nc3 {Black can think of} b5 $5 {already:} 22. Nxb5
Nd3 23. Bxd3 Qxd5 {with strong initiative.}) 21... Bf5 $1 {Planning ...Nd3.}
22. Rxf5 ({A desperate attack.} 22. Qd4 Rc8 {fails questioning Black's
stability.}) 22... gxf5 23. Ng3 Ng6 24. Bd4 Qxd5 25. Nxf5 Bc5 26. Bxc5 Qxc5+
27. Kh1 Re6 $19 {Black has parried all threats and had little trouble winning.}
28. Qh5 Kh8 29. Qh6 Qf8 30. Qg5 Rae8 31. Nh6 Re1+ 32. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 33. Kh2 Qd6+
0-1

