{[#]White's control over the light squares seems to offer him an advantage.
Can you prove this wrong?} 22... b5 $1 {Indeed, it is essential to drive the
enemy queen away from the a2-g8 diagonal.} ({If} 22... Nxd5 $6 23. fxg6 {
the g6-pawn is taboo due to the pin while if} Nf4 24. gxf7+ (24. Nce4 Nxg6 25.
Nxh5 Rd4 26. Qc2 {with initiative is also interesting.}) 24... Qxf7 25. Qxf7+
Kxf7 26. Nxh5 Bh8 $14 {with playable, but worse position for Black.}) ({
For once} 22... e4 {does not solve the problems after} 23. fxg6 fxg6 24. Ngxe4
$14) 23. axb5 axb5 24. Qxc5 {Relatively best.} (24. Nxb5 Qxd5 $17) (24. Qxb5
Qxb5 25. Nxb5 Nxd5 $17) (24. Qb3 Nxd5 25. fxg6 fxg6 26. Rd1 $2 c4 $1 27. Qxb5
Qxb5 28. Nxb5 e4 $19) 24... Nxd5 25. Qxb5 ({This hands in the initiative to
Black. A better chance for approximate equality was} 25. fxg6 fxg6 26. Nge4 Nf4
27. Ra1 $5 Nd3 28. Qxb5 Qxb5 29. Nxb5 Rf8 30. Rxf8+ Rxf8 31. b3 Nf2+ 32. Nxf2
Rxf2 $11) 25... Qxb5 26. Nxb5 Rb8 27. Nd6 Red8 28. Nc4 h4 ({Even stronger was} 
28... Rdc8 $1 {for if} 29. Nxe5 h4 $1 $17 {the e5-knight is hanging.}) 29. Ne4
Rb4 30. b3 $1 Nf4 $15 {With preferable play for Black already.} 0-1

