{In the current article I will highlight a few typical aspects of Black's
ambitions on the territory supposed to be mainly "White's". Usually Black is
entitled fighting for kingside space and initiative if White has transferred
some of his pieces from this wing to the queenside, in order to prevent
Black's expansion or has neglected development for the sake of pursuing other
practical purposes. Since White's global plan involves in principle f2-f4 at
some stage of the game, a logical black antidote is the blocking ...g6-g5.
True, this weakens the f5-square but maneuvering the knight there is not
always easy, while the light-squared bishop usually offers a satisfactory
defense. The following game was the first one in which Black carried out this
plan at a high level. The final result was disappointing but the plan itself
proved entirely sound.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 c5 3. d5 e6 4. c4 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6.
Nc3 g6 7. e4 Bg7 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Nd2 {This is an important classical
tabiya. White's position is very flexible strategically, but dynamically the
queenside development's delay may count.} Nbd7 11. Qc2 Ne5 {A harmonious move,
activating the knight and clearing the diagonal for the c8-bishop. With his
development incomplete, White should refrain from an early f2-f4 in view of ...
Ne5-g4 with dangerous threats.} 12. b3 $5 {The main drawback of the plan
initiated by this move is that it does not really neutralize the g7-bishop.
The white bishop will hit on the e5-knight and will be exposed to some
tactical tricks as we will see.[#]} ({Some negative effects of the early queen
development can be felt after} 12. h3 g5 {, when Black would be ready to
continue his attack with ...h7-h5.}) ({***} 12. a4 {followed by Ra3 is
considered best.}) 12... g5 $1 13. Bb2 g4 {The g6-pawn has reached g4 almost
by force. ***Both sides' regrouping in the next phase looks logical. Black
tries to take over the initiative, while White is mainly defending against the
immediate threats, relying on the fact that his space advantage would tell in
the long run.} 14. Rfe1 Nh5 15. Nd1 Nf4 16. Bb5 $5 {The win of one tempo is
relative. The bishop is exposed to b5 and will have to retreat later.} Rf8 17.
Ne3 Qg5 {[#]After the activation of the black queen, the maneuvering phase is
approaching its end. In the presence of such threats as .. .Ne5-f3+, concrete
play is likely to start soon.} 18. Nf5 $6 {This move should lose a pawn but
has the merit that it changes the character of the fight at once, something
Mecking might not have been prepared for. White's choice was by far not easy.
Apart from different knight jumps, Black also threatens to get queenside space
with ...a6 followed by ...b5.} (18. Bf1 {was recommended, over defending g2 in
order to prevent ...Nf3+. However, after} Ned3 19. Bxd3 (19. Bxg7 $2 {loses
material to} Nxe1 20. Qc3 Qxg7 $17) 19... Bxb2 20. Rad1 Bd4 $15 {Black's
beautiful bishop ensures him the better play.}) ({***} 18. a4 {does not really
prevent ...Ned3, but offers Black the possibility of} Nf3+ {as well:} 19. Nxf3
({The only move.} 19. gxf3 $2 {leads to mate after:} gxf3+ 20. Kh1 Bh3 21. Bf1
Bg2+ 22. Bxg2 fxg2+ 23. Kg1 Nh3#) 19... gxf3 20. g3 Bxb2 21. Qxb2 {White has
almost stabilized the position, but Black still has some tricks:} Nh3+ 22. Kh1
Qe5 23. Qxe5 (23. Qc2 {is insufficient in view of} Qxe4 $1) 23... Nxf2+ 24. Kg1
Nh3+ 25. Kf1 dxe5 {The position remains unclear, offering chances to both
players.}) ({***The developing move} 18. Rad1 {would parry all the tactical
threats, but not the queenside expansion.[#]} a6 (18... Ned3 $2 {is
ineffective because after} 19. Bxd3 Bxb2 20. Ndc4 $16 {there is no hanging
rook on a1.}) (18... Nf3+ $6 {does not work out so well as before, either:} 19.
Nxf3 gxf3 20. g3 Bxb2 21. Qxb2 Nh3+ 22. Kh1 Qe5 23. Qc2 Qxe4 24. Bd3 $1 $16 {
This is why the rook is needed on d1! Black does not have 24...Qxd3 and the
opening of the e-file largely favor White, who is better developed.}) 19. Bf1
b5 {Black has nothing to complain about, but the game is very much on.}) 18...
Bxf5 19. exf5 {[#]} Ned3 $6 {Black's problem is that he has to choose between
several tempting continuations.} ({The greedy} 19... Nxd5 $6 {would offer
White very active play in the center:} 20. Ne4 $1 Qxf5 21. Rad1 $44) ({***The
best continuation was} 19... Nf3+ $1 20. Nxf3 gxf3 21. g3 Bxb2 22. Qxb2 Qxf5 {
followed by ...Ng6-e5.This was not too difficult to calculate and in the final
position, Black is a pawn up and in complete control of the situation. But
Mecking once confessed me that he had partly lost his confidence because he
was trailing in the match for many days already.}) 20. Bxd3 Bxb2 21. Rad1 {
[#]White has completed his development, the b2-bishop is hanging and the
threat of Ne4 is in the air. Concrete action is needed.} Bd4 $6 {But Mecking
is not prepared for it, or maybe he simply misjudged the position, thinking
that he can still hope for an advantage.} ({He could have forced a draw with:} 
21... Nh3+ $1 22. gxh3 (22. Kf1 $2 {leads to a strong attack after} Nxf2 $1 23.
Kxf2 Bd4+ 24. Kf1 Qf4+) 22... gxh3+ 23. Kf1 Qg2+ 24. Ke2 Qg4+ {White has to
take the perpetual with 25.Kf1, since} 25. f3 $2 {loses after} Qg2+ 26. Ke3
Bd4+ 27. Kf4 Qxh2+ 28. Kg4 Kh8 {followed by ...Rg8+.}) 22. Ne4 $1 {Kortschnoj
immediately grabs his chance.} Qxf5 {[#]After this forced move, the f5-square,
which had been weakened at the start of Black's opening plan, becomes once
again available for the white pieces.} 23. Ng3 $1 {Quite probably, Mecking
underestimated this strong move, which places the knight in a stable position
and takes the weak queenside squares under control.} ({He might have expected} 
23. Nxd6 Qxd5 {, with a promising domination in the center.}) 23... Qg5 (23...
Qxd5 {would just clear the light squares for the enemy bishop>} 24. Bxh7+ Kh8
25. Be4 Qg5 26. Bxb7 $14 {Despite his seeming activity, Black does not have
clear targets. In the long run, the weakness of the light squares is likely to
tell.}) 24. Bxh7+ Kh8 25. Qf5 $1 {[#]Finally the weakness of the f5-square
starts telling. Having finally taken over the initiative Kortschnoj
confidently converted it into a win.} Qh6 $6 ({True, after} 25... Qxf5 26. Bxf5
Nxd5 27. Bxg4 Nc3 28. Rd2 Rae8 29. Rxe8 Rxe8 30. Kf1 {White's position is
slightly preferable. Black's piece activity is temporary (Ng3-f5 will arrive
soon), while his pawns are less mobile than White's. Still, the presence of
opposite bishops may eventually lead to a draw.}) 26. Qxg4 $1 {"Kortschnoj
does not miss such opportunities!" (Taimanov)} Nxg2 $5 {Mecking must have put
big hopes into this blow, but with a knight on g3 the white king is absolutely
safe.} ({If} 26... Kxh7 27. Nf5 {White retrieves the piece with an obvious
advantage.}) 27. Kxg2 Qxh7 28. Re7 Rg8 29. Qf4 $5 Be5 30. Qf3 Rg7 31. Rxb7 Qc2
32. Re1 Kg8 33. Re4 Rf8 34. Rg4 Qxa2 35. Nf5 Rxg4+ 36. Qxg4+ Kh7 37. Qh5+ Kg8
38. Nh6+ ({A quicker win was} 38. Qg5+ Kh7 39. Qh6+ Kg8 40. Ne7#) 38... Kg7 39.
Nxf7 Rg8 {[#]} 40. Nxe5+ ({And now there was nothing wrong with} 40. Qh6# {
, of course.}) 40... Kf6+ 41. Ng4+ Rxg4+ 42. Qxg4 {White wins the game and the
match.} 1-0

