{Another closely related pattern features the h-pawn joining the fight for a
kingside blockade as in the next game:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6
5. Be2 O-O 6. Bg5 c5 7. d5 h6 8. Be3 e6 9. Qd2 exd5 10. cxd5 Re8 11. f3 {
[#]Due to the strong battery along the c1-h6 diagonal and Black's slight delay
in development it would be premature settling for ...g6-g5, as White could
break with h2-h4, getting excellent attacking chances. Kasparov will advance
his g-pawn only after thorough preparing, helped by Wite's slight problems
with developing his kingside.} h5 12. a4 a6 13. a5 Nh7 14. Bd1 Nd7 15. Nge2 Ne5
16. b3 Qh4+ {Before playing ...g6-g5 it is useful deviating the bishop away
from the active diagonal.} 17. Bf2 Qf6 18. Qe3 h4 $1 {[#]In view of the
vulnerability of the f3-pawn White is forced weakening his dark squares
chronically.} 19. h3 g5 {Everything is prepared for this thematic move now.}
20. O-O Bd7 21. Kh1 Nf8 $1 {Since White does not have pressure along the c1-h6
diagonal, the knight is free for the transfer to the optimal g6-square,
joining his colleague in the fight for the dark squares.} 22. Bg1 {It may seem
that White has been outplayed completely but Seirawan keeps his cold blood. He
transfers the bishop to h2 in order to partly reduce Black's control on dark
squares.} Nfg6 23. Bh2 {[#]Black has reached an optimal kingside regrouping
and time has come for defining his future plans.} c4 {A very committal but not
necessarily bad move. Black intends widening the activity area for his knights
but clears the g1-a7 diagonal and the b-file for White, offering him ideas for
counterplay.} ({The consequences of the spectacular} 23... g4 24. f4 Nf3 $5 {
are not clear either:} 25. Rxf3 ({This well-timed exchange sacrifice
neutralizes Black's initiative. If} 25. gxf3 $2 g3 26. Bg1 Bxh3 27. Re1 Bh6 {
the bishop may soon land on f4 with the lethal threat ...g3-g2 mate.}) 25...
gxf3 26. Qxf3 Bb5 27. Ra2 {White's compact center compensates for the missing
exchange. Sadly, Black has lost his blockade.}) ({The most neutral way of
making progress was} 23... Rab8 24. Bc2 b5 25. axb6 Rxb6 {possibly followed by
...Bh6 and ...Nf4 with an active play on both wings. White should refraifrom}
26. f4 $2 {due to} gxf4 27. Nxf4 ({Giving up the dark-squared bishop with} 27.
Bxf4 Nxf4 {would leave him badly exposed.}) 27... Ng4 28. hxg4 Qxc3 $17) 24.
Rb1 {[#]} Rac8 $6 (24... Rec8 {was more restrictive, preventing the next game
move. If} 25. Qb6 Rab8 {Black keeps his stability, even though his active
prospects are somewhat restricted now.}) 25. Qa7 Nf4 $6 {Allowing White
stabilizing the kingside.} 26. bxc4 Nxc4 27. Rxb7 $2 ({The correct move order
was} 27. Bxf4 $1 gxf4 28. Rxb7 {when in the absence of pawn breaks or
constructs blockade on dark squares might not necessarily have compensated for
the missing pawn and White's queenside activity.}) 27... Nd2 $1 28. Rg1 {[#]}
Nxh3 $1 {Seirawan must have thought that this was not dangerous due to his
next intermediate move but analysis proves White is in trouble.} 29. e5 $1 ({If
} 29. Rxd7 Ra8 30. Qb6 Nc4 {White loses the queen as he cannot give up
controlling f2.}) ({Or if} 29. gxh3 Qxf3+ 30. Rg2 Bxh3 31. Qf2 Bxg2+ 32. Qxg2
Qxg2+ 33. Kxg2 Bxc3 {with decisive material advantage.}) 29... Rxe5 $5 {
Thematically the simplest, but objectively by far not the best.} ({True,
things are not entirely clear after} 29... dxe5 {either:} 30. Rxd7 Nxg1 (30...
Ra8 {already does not work:} 31. Qe3 Nc4 32. Ne4 $1 $16 {After having cleared
the e4-square White has this intermediate move defebding f2.}) 31. Qxg1 Nxf3
32. Ne4 Qf5 33. gxf3 Qxd7 34. Qxg5 {with very unclear play where White is not
worse at all.}) ({But the calm} 29... Qf5 $1 {would have won.} 30. e6 ({
Both players must have thought this unclear but it is not. If} 30. Bc2 Qxc2 31.
gxh3 Nxf3 {Black's attack is likely to break through first.}) 30... Ra8 31.
exd7 (31. exf7+ Qxf7 {is no better}) 31... Red8 {winning the queen according
to the known pattern.}) 30. Rxd7 {The rest of the game was probably played in
mutual time trouble.} Nxg1 31. Qxg1 (31. Bxe5 Qxe5 32. Kxg1 g4 {offers Black
reasonable compensation.}) 31... Ree8 32. Rxd6 Qf5 33. Ba4 Qd3 (33... Re7 $1)
34. Bxe8 Rxe8 35. Rc6 h3 36. Bg3 ({After} 36. gxh3 $1 Nxf3 37. Qg2 {Black's
compensation for the piece might have been hard proving.}) 36... hxg2+ 37. Qxg2
Nxf3 38. d6 Re6 39. Qf2 g4 40. Rc8+ Kh7 41. Nf4 Rh6+ 42. Kg2 Ne1+ 43. Kg1 Nf3+
1/2-1/2

