{It is easy to understand that, apart from gaining space, the advance of the
g-pawn is aiming to secure Black's control over the dark squares (e5 and f4
mainly). This can be effective not only if White delays his kingside play, but
also if he rushes in with space gaining.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5
exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. g3 Bg7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Na6 10. h3 Re8 11. Nd2
Nc7 12. a4 b6 13. Nc4 Ba6 14. Na3 Qd7 {The fianchetto system does not put
early pressure on Black but is less inoffensive than it may look. If White
manages to advance his central pawns in the middlegame his g2-bishop may prove
very strong.} 15. Re1 b5 16. axb5 Nxb5 17. Naxb5 Bxb5 18. e4 Rab8 19. Ra3 Qc7
20. Be3 a6 21. Qc2 Nd7 22. f4 c4 23. Qf2 {[#]Both sides have consequently
carried out the mutual plans on opposite wings and play is about equal. But
Black's next move is questionable.} f5 $6 {This fails to create threats or
restricting White's kingside initiative. On the contrary, it weakens the light
squares, offering White additional ideas. ***More about this thematic break
later.} ({True,} 23... Nc5 $2 {intending to occupy the dream d3-square is
premature due to} 24. Bxc5 Qxc5 25. Qxc5 dxc5 26. e5 $16) ({But Black could
prepare it with} 23... Rbc8 {since} 24. Nxb5 axb5 25. Ra6 {is not that
dangerous:} Ra8 26. Rc6 Qb8 {Black has defended all his weaknesses and plans
to continue his plan with ...Ra2.}) 24. g4 $2 {White is impatient punishing
his opponent's last move. True, if allowed playing g4-g5 he would more or less
paralyze Black, but he probably overlooked his resource two moves later.} (24.
exf5 $6 {hoping to use the weakness on f5 would not achieve much either after}
gxf5 {[%cal Gd7c5] when the threat ...Nc5 becomes real in the absence of e4-e5.
}) ({But White could and should have slowly increased the pressure to, say,} 
24. Kh2 $5 {Planning to regroup with Raa1, Re2, and so on before taking
concrete measures.} Bxc3 ({What else? Once again the maneuver} 24... Nc5 $2 {
leads to crushing white advantage:} 25. Bxc5 Qxc5 26. Qxc5 dxc5 27. e5 $18) (
24... fxe4 25. Nxe4 {Threatening Ng5-e6.} h6 26. Raa1 $16 {offers White
excellent attacking chances against Black's weakened kingside.}) 25. bxc3 fxe4
26. Ra2 $5 ({Regrouping for a slow attack with g3-g4 etc and gaining a tempo
over} 26. Bd4 {in the next line.}) 26... Nc5 27. Bxc5 Qxc5 28. Qxc5 dxc5 29.
Bxe4 $16 {With obvious white advantage in the ending.}) {[#]} 24... fxg4 $1 25.
hxg4 {If allowed playing g4-g5 White would obtain a crushing space advantage
but Black can avoid it.} g5 $1 {Suddenly Black gains the control over the dark
squares and the g2-bishop is about to become "bad".} 26. fxg5 $6 ({Maybe it
would have been more cautious keeping the position closed with} 26. f5 {
even though Black's play is very pleasant:} Ne5 27. Qg3 Nd3 28. Rf1 Qe7 $15)
26... Ne5 27. Qh4 {Not a pleasant move to play as the queen is far from her
colleagues now, but the alternatives are far from appealing:} (27. Nxb5 Rxb5 {
simultaneously threatening ...Rxb2 and /\...Nxg4.}) (27. Qg3 Bd7 28. Bh3 Rxb2
29. Rxa6 Rb3 $19 {with an unpleasant pin along the third rank.}) {[#]} 27...
Bd7 $1 {A wise retreat, clearing the b-file and attacking g4.} 28. Re2 Bxg4 29.
Rf2 Rf8 (29... Bc8 $5 {defending a6 and threatening ...Ng4 is a serious
alternative.}) 30. Rxa6 Rxf2 31. Qxf2 Rf8 $1 $17 {White's extra pawn does not
make itself felt and Black has very strong initiative.} 32. Qh4 Qb7 33. Ra7
Qxb2 34. g6 hxg6 35. Rxg7+ Kxg7 36. Bh6+ Kg8 37. Bxf8 Qc1+ 38. Kh2 Qf4+ 39. Kg1
Qxf8 40. Qg5 Qb8 41. Qe3 Qb2 42. Kh1 Bh5 43. Bh3 Nf3 44. Be6+ Kh7 45. Qa7+ Kh6
46. Qe3+ g5 47. Ne2 Qe5 48. Qf2 c3 49. Ng3 c2 50. Nf5+ Qxf5 51. Qxc2 0-1

