1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. d5 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Nd2 Bg7 8. e4
O-O 9. Be2 a6 10. a4 Nbd7 11. O-O Ne8 12. Nc4 Ne5 13. Ne3 f5 14. f4 Nf7 15.
exf5 gxf5 {[#]Black has chosen a straightforward plan involving certain risk.
On the positive side White has been deprived forever of the central break and
Black has some chances of using the e4- and g4-squares. Moreover, the
c1-bishop is at least temporary passive. On the other hand, the f5-pawn can
easily turn into a weakness while a rook lift on the third rank may cause some
troubles to the black king.} 16. Bd3 {White decides to play against the
f5-pawn.} ({With hindsight, it may have been better taking measures against
the queenside play with} 16. a5 Bd7 17. Nc4 {Black would probably have
continued with} Nc7 {folloed by ...Nb5-d4, but all in all White would have
maintained his stability.}) 16... Nh6 17. Qc2 Bd7 18. Ne2 {[#]} Qe7 ({Black's
attention, too, was captured by the kingside. Simpler was} 18... b5 {for
instance} 19. Ng3 Bd4 20. Kh1 Ng7 {with active queenside counterplay and
relative kingside stability.}) 19. Kh1 Nf6 ({Switching back to the queenside
plan would be too slow already:} 19... Rb8 20. Bd2 b5 21. axb5 axb5 22. Ng3 Qf7
23. Ra7 {combining threats on both wings.}) 20. Ng3 Ne4 $5 {[#]Both sides' the
play was consequent in the last phase and the tension has reached its apogee.
White faces a difficult choice.} 21. Bxe4 $6 {It is obvious that this weakens
the light squares but Lupulescu must have relied on the line played in the
game, overlooking the 24th move. ***In order to understand how complicated the
positon really is here are the main alternatives among which only the last one
seems offering chances for fighting for an advantage:} (21. Nexf5 $6 Nxf5 22.
Nxe4 (22. Bxe4 Nxg3+ 23. hxg3 Bd4 $17 {puts the white king in big danger along
the h-file.}) 22... Nd4 23. Qb1 (23. Qd1 {is worse:} c4 24. Bb1 Nb3 $15) 23...
Rae8 {Black's advance in development compensates for the missing pawn.}) (21.
Nxe4 $6 fxe4 22. Bxe4 Bd4 {also leavs White hanging and underdeveloped.}) ({
The critical continuation is} 21. Ngxf5 $5 Nxf5 22. Bxe4 Nd4 23. Bxh7+ Kh8 24.
Qd3 Bh6 25. Bg6 Rxf4 26. Bd2 Raf8 {Black is very active but White keeps his
extra pawn and a normal regrouping.}) 21... fxe4 22. Nxe4 ({Or if} 22. Qxe4 Qh4
23. Qf3 Rae8 {with strong initiative.}) 22... Bd4 23. Ng5 Ng4 {[#]} 24. Nxg4 $2
({This careless move immediately puts White on the verge of defeat. He should
have tried defending with} 24. Rf3 Rae8 25. Ra3 {even though his position
looks very on the edge.}) 24... Qxg5 $1 $17 ({The point. Black wins the
d5-pawn obtaining a dangerous central majority and piece activity. White might
have expected} 24... Bxg4 $2 25. Bd2 $16 {followed by Bc3.}) 25. Rf3 $2 {
[#]Allowing an immediate win.} Qxd5 $2 $15 ({Black misses} 25... Qxg4 $1 26.
Rg3 Qxg3 27. hxg3 Bg4 $19 {with the imparable threats ...Rh5 or ...Rf6.}) 26.
Ne3 $6 ({Wite should have looked for counterchances with} 26. f5 $5 $15) 26...
Rae8 $17 {[#]Two bishops and central domination offer Black all chances to win.
} 27. Bd2 Qe4 28. Qc1 Rxf4 29. Rxf4 Qxf4 30. Nc2 Qe4 31. Nxd4 cxd4 32. Bb4 Bc6
33. Qd2 d3 34. h3 Qg6 0-1

