{[#]Black plans the familiar ...Qf6 followed by ...Nf4 so White decided to
force matters with} 17. g4 {Your answer?} Nf4 $1 {The thematical and at the
same time strongest move.} (17... Nf6 {would offer Wite the time to organize
his queenside counterplay with} 18. a5 {. After the game move White is forced
picking up the gauntlet.}) 18. Bxf4 gxf4 19. Qxf4 h5 $1 {Another fine move,
shattering White's apparently strong structure.} 20. Qg3 ({Trying to keep the
central flexibility. If} 20. gxh5 Kh7 {followed by ...Bh6 offers Black strong
attack (Psakhis).}) (20. h3 {weakens the king too much, for instance} hxg4 21.
hxg4 Ng6 22. Qg3 Bd4+ 23. Kg2 Kg7 {followed by ...Rh8.}) (20. g5 f6 21. g6 f5 {
is also hopeless for White.}) 20... hxg4 21. f4 Ng6 22. f5 ({In their comments
for the Chess Informant Psakhis and Vaisser recommends} 22. Bd3 $5 {but after}
f5 23. exf5 Nh4 {Black takes the control of all the important squares.}) 22...
Bd4+ $1 23. Kh1 Bxc3 24. Qxg4 $5 (24. bxc3 $2 Qxe4+ 25. Kg1 Qxb1 26. Bd3 Qb6
27. a5 Qd8 28. fxg6 fxg6 $19 {Psakhis, Vaisser.}) 24... Bg7 25. Rg1 Rae8 26.
Bd3 Qe5 27. Qg5 Bxa4 $19 {White will sooner or later have to retrieve the
piece, but this will not help as his position is strategically lost.} 0-1

