{[#]Black started his counterplay with} 14... f5 {Instead of the obvious 15.
exf5 White answered with} 15. f4 Nf7 16. exf5 {Is there any way of taking
advantage of this concrete move order?} Nh6 $5 {A logical move. Black is more
concerned about keeping the f5-square for his pieces than retrieving the pawn.}
({But} 16... Bd4 $1 {is a more restrictive move order:} 17. fxg6 (17. Rf3 Nh6 {
does not make much of a difference with respect to the game.}) 17... Nh6 {
transposing below.}) 17. fxg6 $2 ({White misses his chance to stay in the game:
} 17. Kh1 $1 Nxf5 18. Nxf5 Bxf5 19. Bf3 Qh4 20. g4 Bd7 {Black's position is
pleasant but there are no big worries for White either.}) 17... Bd4 18. gxh7+
Kh8 19. Rf3 (19. Qd3 Bf5 $17) 19... Ng4 20. Qd3 Qh4 21. h3 Nxe3 22. Rxe3 (22.
Bxe3 Rxe3 $1 23. Rxe3 Qxf4 24. Rf1 (24. Nd1 $2 {loses material without any
shadow of compensation:} Nxd5 25. Ra3 Bf5 26. Qd2 Nxe3 27. Nxe3 Re8 $19) 24...
Qxe3+ 25. Qxe3 Bxe3+ 26. Kh1 Bd7 27. Rf7 Rd8 $17 {Black will need some time to
neutralize White's activity but in principle, there is no real compensation
for the piece.}) 22... Qxf4 23. Nd1 Nxd5 $19 24. Ra3 Nxe3 25. Nxe3 Bf5 26. Qb3
Bxh7 27. Kh1 Be5 28. Kg1 Qh2+ 29. Kf2 Bg3+ 30. Kf3 Be4+ 31. Kg4 Rg8+ 0-1

