{In the previous articles we have focused on several global aspects: how to
handle structures on either board sector, or how to coordinate the minor
pieces. But for the Benoni player the main treasure is, of course, the
g7-bishop. As mentioned before, the minor piece coordination (with the
inevitable conflict caused by the lack of space) mainly refers to the knights
and the queen's bishop. The king's bishop has a life of its own and does not
stand in the way of its colleagues. But of course in order to make it an
effective attacking element, it usually needs help from the rest of the army.
In this article, we will examine a few examples in which the bishop's
domination along the dark diagonals is telling. The most typical cases are
when it faces the opposition of the white light-squared bishop. We have met
such a situation towards the end of the game Parligras-Gashimov, in the
article dedicated to piece play. We will now see an even more pure example,
with very little material left on board, when the difference between bishops
is overwhelming. There is an anecdote related to this game illustrating what
is going to happen on board. I had a good start in the tournament 3/3 and
played the fourth game on my birthday. I used to win all my games on such
occasions and was happy thinking of such an initial advantage against a strong
opponent (in those years Danailov was an active player even though he had
already started coaching the very young Topalov). I smiled when congratulated
by the arbiters on my arrival at the board, but was stunned when a few minutes
later they also congratulated Silvio! Oh no, what a coincidence (arbiters were
also shocked when realizing it!), and what a pity I could not count on my
"initial advantage" anymore! But as the game suggests, Danailov must have
belonged to the category of players who lose their birthday games. He played
highly "cooperative", an element that makes many of the old games so
instructive. The same kind of difference could be noticed in the dialogue
between our bishops in the final part of the game.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 d6
4. Nc3 g6 5. e4 Bg7 6. f3 O-O 7. Be3 e6 8. Nge2 exd5 9. cxd5 Nbd7 10. Ng3 a6
11. a4 h5 12. Be2 h4 13. Nf1 Nh7 14. g4 f5 15. gxf5 gxf5 {[#]} 16. Rg1 $2 {
An awful move, allowing me setting up the blockade on dark squares.} (16. Qd2 {
or even}) (16. exf5 {would have been preferable, although Black would have
nothing to complain about.}) 16... f4 17. Bf2 Ng5 18. Nd2 Nh3 {Ansuring the
bishop's unchallenged domination on dark squares.} 19. Rg4 Nxf2 20. Kxf2 Ne5
21. Rg1 Kh8 22. Kg2 h3+ 23. Kh1 Qh4 24. a5 Bd7 25. Na4 {The start of a long
series of exchanges leading to the thematic ending.} Bxa4 26. Rxa4 Rg8 27. Qe1
Bf6 {Since the long diagonal is obstructed by a wonderful knight, the bishop
gladly looks for new horizons, at least temporarily.} 28. Qxh4+ Bxh4 29. Raa1
Bf2 30. Rxg8+ Rxg8 31. Nc4 Nxc4 32. Bxc4 Bd4 {[#]This is the start of the
thematic phase. Black's advantage is obvious, but due to the opposite-colored
bishops one may think (and I also had some doubts) that White has drawing
chances. In the first phase, the rooks' presence is decisive, though, as
White's king is in a permanent mating set. The bishop's activity is
overwhelming. It ensures the control over the g-file, keeps b2 under pressure
and turns the a5-pawn into a permanent target.} 33. Rb1 Rg2 34. b3 {White
continues playing "cooperatively, as if he really enjoyed witnessing the
execution.} ({Even though this would not have saved the game, he should have
tried one of the thematic breaks.} 34. e5 $5 Bxe5 35. Bf1 $5 {The only moment
when this is possible.} Rf2 ({This is what I would probably have chosen in the
game as the ending resulting after} 35... Rxb2 36. Rxb2 Bxb2 37. Bxh3 {is not
easy to evaluate over the board. In fact, Black seems to be winning.} c4 38.
Kg2 Bc3 39. Kf1 Bxa5 40. Ke2 {anticipating ...c4-c3-c2 when Kd2 would be
impossible.} Kg7 41. Bc8 Kf6 42. Bxb7 Ke5 {One way or another Black will have
two passed pawns and the reserve f4-pawn ensures the win after forcing White
giving up his bishop.}) 36. Bxh3 Bxb2 37. Kg1 (37. Bc8 c4 {promotes.}) 37...
Bd4 38. Kh1 c4 39. Rxb7 c3 40. Rc7 c2 41. Kg1 Rd2+ 42. Kf1 Bc5 {The hero
bishop cut off the rook.}) ({The other attempt was} 34. b4 $5 cxb4 35. e5 Bxe5
36. Rxb4 Rf2 37. Rb1 (37. Rxb7 {loses the bishop to} Rc2 {for instance} 38. Bf1
Rc1 39. Kg1 Bd4+) 37... Rxf3 38. Rb3 Rf2 39. Rxh3+ Kg7 40. Bd3 Ra2 41. Rh7+ Kf6
42. Rxb7 f3 43. Rb1 Rd2 $1 {Forcing the bishop to leave the a6-pawn alone for
if} 44. Bxa6 Rxh2+ 45. Kg1 f2+ 46. Kf1 Rh1+ {the rook remains undefended.}) {
[#]} 34... Rf2 35. Rf1 Rb2 $5 ({I was aware of the possible white counterplay
so, for the time being, I decided to prevent b3-b4. The a5-pawn can wait. If} 
35... Ra2 36. Rb1 Rxa5 37. Bf1 {Black should win anyway, but some accuracy is
needed. The last move, tying up the bishop to the defence of the b3-pawn, is
also the engines' favorite.}) 36. Rc1 Kg7 37. Rd1 Kf6 38. Rc1 Rf2 {Now that
the king has approached the center, I was less worried about White's
counterplay.} 39. Rf1 {[#]} Ra2 {Once again I refused relying on calculation
and sometimes by just one tempo. I believe this is the most technical approach.
} ({But the difference between bishops is so big that exchanging rooks would
have also won:} 39... Rxf1+ 40. Bxf1 Bc3 41. Bxh3 Bxa5 42. Bc8 Bd8 43. Bxb7 a5
44. Ba6 Ke5 {The king's intrusion is decisive.} 45. Kg2 Kd4 46. Kf1 (46. Be2
Kc3 47. Bd1 Kd2 {tragicomically traps the bishop.}) 46... Kc3 47. Ke1 (47. Bc4
{If} a4) 47... Kxb3 48. Be2 $5 {The only chance.} a4 49. Bd1+ Kb4 50. Kd2 a3
51. Kc1 Bf6 52. Kb1 Kc3 53. Ka2 Kd2 54. Bb3 Ke2 {Black will soon win the
bishop for the f-pawn.}) 40. Rb1 Rxa5 41. Bf1 Ra2 42. Bxh3 b5 {Time trouble is
over and disgusted with the perspective of two queenside pawns by complete own
passiveness, Silvio resigned.} 0-1

