{Typically, the best squares for the bishop are e5 and d4, as it keeps both
wings under pressure. But since on e5 it usually supposes being a blocking
piece, an issue covered before, we should focus on the d4-square. We have seen
how effective my bishop was in the endgame, but things can be similar with
almost all pieces on board.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6
6. Nf3 g6 7. e4 Bg7 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Nd2 Na6 11. Re1 Nc7 12. a4 b6 13.
Qc2 {[#]Play has been more or less normal so far, but we should notice that
with his 11th and 13th move White has transferred two major pieces farther
from the king. This is a sign already that he should be careful.} Ng4 $6 {
This is possible after the queen departs from d1, but, as we will see, not
best.} ({Black could have tried either} 13... Na6 {taking advantage of the
queen's exposure}) ({or} 13... Nd7 14. Nc4 Ne5 {with adequate play in both
cases.}) 14. h3 $2 {After this careless move Tal will magnificently make use
of the absence of kingside defenders.} (14. Bxg4 $1 Bxg4 15. Nc4 {would have
offered White a stable advantage, for instance} Bc8 16. Bf4 Bf8 17. b3 Ba6 18.
Qd2 $14 {Black cannot free himself easily since the exchange of the active
knight only strengthens White's center after bxc4.}) {[#]} 14... Nxf2 $1 15.
Kxf2 ({There was no adequate way of declining the sacrifice.} 15. Rf1 Nxh3+ 16.
gxh3 Bxh3 17. Nf3 Bxf1 18. Kxf1 Qd7 $17 {with a material advantage and
attacking chances.}) (15. Nf3 {may have been the best practical chance, though.
} Bxc3 16. bxc3 Nxe4 $15 {White would have enough compensation for just one
pawn, but not for two. Still, the game remains double-edged.}) 15... Qh4+ 16.
Kf1 (16. g3 {offers Black a forced win already:} Bd4+ 17. Kf3 Qh5+ 18. Kg2
Bxh3+ 19. Kh1 Bg4+ 20. Kg2 Qh3#) 16... Bd4 17. Nd1 {[#]} Qxh3 $1 ({Better than
} 17... Bxh3 {when White may hope to put up resistance with} 18. Ra3 $5) 18.
Bf3 Qh2 {One may think that in view of the knight sacrifice and the queen
pseudo-sacrifice the game has a tactical character, thus not being suited for
an article about strategy. But there is an important detail. The difficult
part was not finding the spectacular moves but evaluating the current position.
White seems to be well coordinated (especially after the rook lift to a3, and
yet he is completely lost. The combined pressure of the bishop and queen (and
soon of all the remaining pieces) and on the other hand White's impossibility
of transferring pieces to the kingside, leave the king in deadly trouble.
Gurgenidze obviously underestimated all these when provoking the sacrifice on
f2. In the last phase, Tal's play flows naturally and easily. No tactics, just
slow regrouping, meaning strategy.} 19. Ne3 f5 20. Ndc4 fxe4 21. Bxe4 Ba6 {
It is always better when the other bishop joins the party on neighboring
diagonal. Both knights are pinned now.} 22. Bf3 Re5 23. Ra3 Rae8 24. Bd2 Nxd5
25. Bxd5+ Rxd5 26. Ke2 {[#]Not a realistic attempt to escape.} Bxe3 ({The last
two moves in the game are thematical. After having kept the opponent under
pressure using his bishop, Tal exchanges both of them to deliver the decisive
blow. But there are many winning moves already, for instance} 26... Qh5+ {
focing the king to return to the dangerous area.}) 27. Rxe3 Bxc4+ (27... Bxc4+
{In view of} 28. Qxc4 Qxg2+ {mating White resigned.}) 0-1

