{The following example is even more stunning. The bishop's domination was
partly compensating for a huge material deficit, causing White bit practical
problems and eventually yielding Black a win.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4.
Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. O-O Na6 10. Nd2 Nb4 11.
Be2 Re8 12. a3 Na6 13. Re1 Nc7 14. Qc2 Rb8 15. a4 b6 16. Nb5 $6 a6 17. Nxc7
Qxc7 18. Ra2 Qe7 19. f3 Nh5 20. Nf1 f5 21. Bd3 f4 {[#]It is easy to establish
that Black has outplayed his opponent completely. But this will not be an
example about blockade...} 22. g4 Bd4+ 23. Kh1 Qh4 24. Re2 Qh3 25. Rg2 Qxf3 ({
Objectively, this spoils most of the advantage. But had the game continued with
} 25... Nf6 $17 {followed by ...g6-g5 and ...h7-h5 things would have been by
far less exciting and instructive.}) 26. Nd2 $1 ({Suddenly the queen does not
have good squares to avoid the perpetual attacking. Tal must have counted on} 
26. gxh5 Rxe4 $1 {Threatening ...Re1.} 27. Be2 Rxe2 $1 28. Qxe2 Qxe2 29. Rxe2
Bb7 {The second bishop joins the party with decisive effect.} 30. Ne3 ({
Relatively better than} 30. Ra3 Bxd5+ 31. Rg2 Re8 {folowed by ...Re2 or ...Re1.
}) 30... fxe3 31. Ra3 Bxd5+ 32. Kg1 Bc4 {White has to return the exchange on
e3, leading to a lost ending with two pawns down.}) 26... Qe3 27. Nf1 Qf3 {
As we will see, this is not an acceptance of the indirect draw offer.} ({
Things are not entirely clear after} 27... Qe1 28. Bd2 Qh4 29. gxh5 Bh3 30. Bc3
{neutralizing the bishop with every chance to survive.}) 28. Nd2 {[#]} Bxg4 $3
{The evaluation refers to the courage, as objectively the move should lose.}
29. Nxf3 Bxf3 {It is easy to understand Tal's frustration when realizing
things have gone wrong from an excellent position. But most (if not all other)
players would have accepted the "inevitable" by making a draw. And yet, the
future World champion (then only an 18-year old talent) preferred playing on
under highly unfavorable material circumstances. The d4-bishop has an opponent,
but the f4-pawn restricts it, so White will need finding the time for b2-b3
and Bb2. The main difference with respect to the previous game is not the
extra queen, but the safer king's position in the corner, allowing White
transferring pieces to help him, even though this will take some time.} 30. h4
{A strong move, avoiding back rank problems.} ({Psakhis analyzes} 30. b3 Rxe4
$1 31. Bxe4 Re8 {(Now is when the back rank counts!)} 32. Qc4 Rxe4 33. h4 Be5
34. Qxa6 Re1+ 35. Kh2 Rxc1 {, assessing the position as complicated. Indeed
after} 36. Rg1 Rc3 $1 {followed by ...Nf6, the network around the white king
more or less ensures a draw:}) 30... Rf8 {[#]An impressively calm move with a
queen down.} 31. Be2 $2 {The losing move, probably fruit wrongly applying the
method of elimination.} ({I assume the first move coming up to mind is
unpinning the rook with} 31. Kh2 {But this offers Black at least adequate
compensation for the queen:} Bxg2 32. Qxg2 f3 33. Qg4 Be5+ 34. Kg1 f2+ 35. Kf1
(35. Kg2 Bf4 {wins one of the bishops, restoring the material equality and
keeping a good position.}) 35... Ng3+ 36. Kg2 f1=Q+ 37. Bxf1 Rxf1 {Once again
material is approximately equal and Black is not worse. This kind of lines
probably induced Birgraber controlling the f3-square with the bishop.}) ({
In fact, there were several moves keeping the advantage to White. My favorite
is} 31. b3 $1 {[%cal Ga2g2] achieving several goals. White clears the second
rank inserting the a2-roo into play, prepares Bb2 (no trapping with Bf4
anymore!) and prevents ...c5-c4 which could cause trouble in certain
situations. But in order to win, White would have had to take a few difficult
decisions, so I believe that from practical point of view Tal's fate in his
bishop and its colleagues was justified.} Rbe8 {Another "quiet" move.} 32. Kh2
$1 ({Paradoxically,} 32. Bb2 {leads only to a draw, by leaving the f4-square
undefended:} Bxg2+ 33. Qxg2 f3 34. Qh3 f2 35. Bxd4 cxd4 36. Ra1 Nf4 $1 {
This would follow with the queen on other squares, too.} 37. Qg3 Nxd3 38. Qxd3
Rf4 39. Rf1 Rexe4 $11 {followed by a perpetual check along the fourth rank.})
32... Bxg2 33. Qxg2 f3 34. Qg4 $1 {The most active move, preparing Qd7 and
controlling f4.} Be5+ ({If} 34... f2 35. Bh6 f1=Q 36. Bxf1 Rxf1 37. Qd7 {
wins. Had White played 34.Qh3, Black would have had 35...Nf4!}) 35. Kg1 f2+ 36.
Kf1 ({A paradoxical move, agreeing to return the remaining material advantage.
But if} 36. Kg2 Nf4+ 37. Bxf4 Rxf4 38. Qg5 Ref8 39. Bf1 {WHite is completely
paralyzed and Black can even become ambitious with, say,} R8f6 $15 {followed
by ...h7-h6.}) 36... Ng3+ 37. Kg2 f1=Q+ 38. Bxf1 Nxf1 ({After b2-b3,} 38...
Rxf1 {does not work due to} 39. Bb2) 39. Qd7 {with a decisive attack.}) 31...
Ng3+ {The start of a forced maneuver winning material.} 32. Kh2 Bxg2 33. Kxg2
Nxe2 34. Qxe2 f3+ 35. Qxf3 Rxf3 36. Kxf3 Rf8+ 37. Kg3 Be5+ 38. Kg2 Bf4 0-1

