{5[#]Black is an exchange up and his position looks active, but the d4-bishop
is attacked and the queen is in dager ofbeing trapped with 21.Re2. Your move.} 
20... Bh3 $1 {Forcing the rook to abandon the initial idea.} 21. Rg1 {/\gxh3+}
Kf8 $6 ({Spectacular but not the best.} 21... Bg4 $1 {would have offered
excellent winning chances.} 22. Nxd4 (22. Rf1 Qe3 {would have maintained the
material advantage}) 22... cxd4 23. Rf1 (23. Nb5 Rxe4 {with a decisive attack.}
) 23... Qh4 24. Nb5 Be2) 22. Nxd4 cxd4 23. f5 $2 {Missing a saving chance.} (
23. Nd1 $2 Bxg2+ 24. Rxg2 Qe1+ 25. Rg1 Qxe4+ 26. Rg2 Qe1+ 27. Rg1 Rac8 28. Qb1
Qe2 $19) (23. gxh3 $2 Qf3+ 24. Rg2 dxc3 25. Bxc3 Rac8 26. Bg7+ Ke7 $19) (23.
Ba3 $1 {A logical move, taking advantage of the missing bishop and the
c5-pan's new location.} Rec8 24. f5 Rxc3 25. Qh6+ Ke8 26. Qxd6 Bxg2+ 27. Rxg2
Qe1+ 28. Rg1 Qxe4+ 29. Rg2 {with a draw (Dvoretzky, Nunn).}) 23... dxc3 24.
Qxc3 (24. Qh6+ Ke7 25. Bxc3 Bxg2+ 26. Rxg2 Qf1+ 27. Rg1 Qf3+ 28. Rg2 Qxc3 {Nunn
}) 24... Rxe4 25. gxh3 Ke8 26. Qd3 Re1 27. Rxe1+ Qxe1+ 28. Kg2 Rc8 29. f6 Kd7
30. Qxh7 Qd2+ 31. Kg3 Qxd5 32. Kh4 Re8 0-1

