{1[#]Few moves earlier, Black (who had only one minute left, without increment)
had sacrificed his passive c7-knight on d5 in order to clear the paths for the
rooks. Possibly influenced by his opponent's time trouble White allowed a
simple combination and lost. In fact, he could have maintained a clear
advantage. How?} 29. Ne4 $4 {A typical blunder in a difficult position from
the practical point of view.} (29. Nb1 $2 {allows an even more beautiful
combination:} Bf3 $3 30. Rxe8+ Qxe8 31. Rxf3 Rxg2+ 32. Kxg2 Qe2+ {mating soon.}
) (29. g4 $6 Bc4 $15 {keeps White under domination despite his material
advantage.}) ({White should have immediately challenged the central bishop:} 
29. Bb2 $3 Rxd2 30. Bxd4 Rxd4 {White might have stopped here when calculating
but} 31. Re3 $1 {could have maintained decent winning chances due to Black's
poor coordination.} Rd2 32. g4 Rc2 33. f5 $16 {Blck cannot free himself easily
and Wite's attack develops naturally.}) 29... Rxe4 $1 30. Bxe4 Bf1+ $1 31. Bxc2
Qxh3# 0-1

