{2[#]White has played the opening carelessly and after} 11... Qh4 12. h3 Nxf2
$5 {he found himself in some sort of trouble. And yet, not everything is lost.
How would you defend?} 13. Kxf2 $2 {When playing this White must have
overlooked Black's 14th move. But abstractly, he should not have allowed his
king being dominated by the d4-bishop!} (13. Rxf2 $1 {offered better chances
of survival:} Qxg3 14. Bf4 Qh4 15. Nb5 a6 16. Nxd6 Bd4 17. Qd2 Bxf2+ 18. Qxf2
Qxf2+ 19. Kxf2 f6 20. Ke3 Nd7 21. Bh6 Rd8 22. Rf1 Ra7 23. Be2 $44 {/\Bg4 with
reasonable compensation for the exchange.}) 13... Bd4+ 14. Kf3 h5 $3 {A
brilliant (not so) quiet move, threatening 15...Bg4+ 16.hxg4 Qxg4 mate.} (14...
Nd7 {is too slow as after} 15. Bf4 {the king manages escaping to the queenside.
}) 15. Nf5 $5 gxf5 16. exf5 Nd7 $17 {And Black continued the attack by
material equality already (0-1).} 0-1

