1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 Bg7 {
Traditionally, this is the most aggressive system in the Benoni. The central
pawns look scary, but White should also take into account the weaknesses left
behind and the time spent on pawn moves. One way in which the early activity
may backfire consists of the white dark-squared bishop remaining passive if
the thematic e4-e5 fails to force ...dxe5.} 8. e5 {This looks threatening but
White has not enough development to sustain such an early initiative. The move
was popular in the past but now almost completely disappeared.} ({In lines 6
and 7 we will cover} 8. Bb5+) ({and in line 8 the main classical line} 8. Nf3)
8... Nfd7 $1 ({The most flexible answer, keeping the d-file closed for if} 8...
dxe5 9. fxe5 Nfd7 10. e6 fxe6 11. dxe6 {White maintains at least some
initiative:} Nf6 (11... Nb6 12. Qxd8+ Kxd8 13. Bg5+ Ke8 14. Bb5+ Nc6 15. Nf3
Bxe6 16. O-O $36 {Getz,N (2353)-Munoz Pantoja,M (2457) Barcelona 2013 (0-1, 44)
}) 12. Qxd8+ Kxd8 13. Bf4 Bxe6 14. O-O-O+ Nbd7 15. Nf3 h6 $6 (15... Nh5 16. Bd6
Re8 {is better and play would remain unclear.}) {Destrebecq,F-Perenyi,B
Belfort 1988 (0-1, 29)} 16. Bd3 g5 17. Bd6 $16) 9. Nb5 {The point behind the
previous move.} (9. Ne4 dxe5 10. Nd6+ {transposes.}) ({With the d-file closed} 
9. e6 fxe6 10. dxe6 Nb6 {just wins a pawn.}) (9. exd6 {releases the tension
too soon to be dangerous.} O-O 10. Nf3 Nf6 11. Be2 Ne8 12. Be3 b6 13. O-O Nxd6
14. Qd2 {Skula,E-Jerabek,Z Czech Republic 1999 (1-0, 53)} Nd7 {With good
development and safe blockade in the centre.}) 9... dxe5 10. Nd6+ Ke7 11. Nxc8+
{Of course, exchanging a piece which has been jumping around a lot for a
bishop which has not moved at all leaves White far behind in development, with
no realistic possibilities of taking advantage of the exposed black king.} (11.
fxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxc8+ Qxc8 {helps Black's development.}) 11... Qxc8 12. Nf3 (12.
d6+ {hands in the c6-square to the knight.} Kf8 13. Nf3 e4 14. Ng5 h6 15. Nxf7
(15. Nxe4 Nc6 16. Bd3 Bd4 $17) 15... Kxf7 16. Bc4+ Kf8 17. f5 Bd4 18. fxg6 Kg7
19. Be6 Qd8 20. Qb3 Qb6 21. Qg3 Nf6 22. Bd2 Qxb2 $19 {Sulava,N (2425)-Namgilov,
S Budapest 1990 (0-1, 27)}) 12... Re8 {This is the main line, preparing ...
e5-e4, but there is a viable alternative:} (12... Rd8 13. fxe5 Nxe5 14. Bg5+
Kf8 15. Bxd8 Qxd8 16. Be2 Nxf3+ 17. Bxf3 Bxb2 18. Rb1 Bc3+ 19. Kf1 Qa5 $36 {
Grandelius,N (2570)-Hedman,E (2381) Falun 2012 (0-1, 50)}) 13. fxe5 {
Eliminating the threat ...e5-e4 but activating Black's pieces.} (13. Bc4 Kf8
14. O-O e4 15. Ng5 Nb6 16. Bb5 Rd8 17. d6 Bd4+ 18. Kh1 {This has been played
in three games, all won by White, but Black is not worse at all:} Qf5 $1 $146 {
more or less forcing the weakening of the long diagonal since otherwise, White
cannot continue his attack with f4-f5.} 19. g4 Qd5 20. f5 Rxd6 21. fxg6 hxg6
22. Rxf7+ Kg8 23. Bf4 Rd7 24. Bxd7 e3+ 25. Qf3 Qxf3+ 26. Nxf3 Kxf7 $15) (13. f5
e4 14. Ng5 Kf8 15. Nxh7+ Kg8 16. fxg6 fxg6 17. Ng5 Ne5 18. Ne6 Nbc6 $5 $146 ({
Even more interesting although not necessarily better than} 18... Rxe6 19. dxe6
Nbc6 20. Qd6 {Pacher,M (2403)-Simacek,P (2462) Czechia 2012 (1-0, 60)} Nb4 $13)
19. Nxg7 Kxg7 20. dxc6 Nd3+ 21. Kd2 Nf2 22. Qb3 e3+ 23. Kc2 e2 {Black will
retrieve the piece in a chaotic ending where his superior activity will
compensate for the missing pawn.} 24. Qc3+ Kh7 25. Qf6 Qe6 26. Qxe6 Rxe6 27.
cxb7 Rb8 28. Bf4 Rxb7 29. Re1 Rbe7 30. Rg1 exf1=Q 31. Rexf1 Re2+ 32. Kb1 Nd3
33. Bc1 Rb7 34. b3 c4 {with t least equal play as} 35. Rf3 cxb3 36. Rxd3 $2
bxa2+ {mates next.}) 13... Nxe5 (13... c4 $5 $146 {prevents the bishop's
activation.}) 14. Bb5 Nbd7 15. Nxe5 Kf8 16. O-O Rxe5 17. Bf4 {Both sides have
played energetically and the postion has almost calmed down.} c4 {I prefer
this from a wide range of playable moves. Black sacrifices the exchange in
orde to slow down White's initiative.} (17... Rf5 18. Bd6+ Kg8 19. Rxf5 gxf5
20. Bxd7 (20. Qf3 $1 $44) 20... Qxd7 21. Bxc5 Bxb2 22. Rb1 Be5 $15 {0-1 (58)
Curtin,E (2200)-Lobron,E (2335) Groningen 1980}) (17... Re4 18. Qf3 f5 19. Rae1
Rxe1 20. Rxe1 a6 21. Bf1 Bd4+ 22. Be3 (22. Kh1 Nf6) 22... Qc7 23. Bxd4 cxd4 24.
Qh3 Nf6 25. Qa3+ Kg8 26. Re7 Qb6 27. Re6 Qa7 28. Bd3 Ne4 $13 {Saint Amour,P 
(2050)-Hase,M (2433) Chessfriend.com 2004 (½-½, 47)}) 18. Qd4 (18. Bxe5 Nxe5
$15) (18. Bxd7 Qxd7 19. Bxe5 Bxe5 20. Qf3 (20. Qd2 Qd6) 20... Re8 21. Rae1 b5
$44) 18... Rh5 19. Qxc4 Nb6 20. Qb4+ Kg8 {Winning the d-pawn soon.} 21. Rac1 (
21. d6 a5 22. Qb3 Qc5+ 23. Be3 Qxd6) {Astolfi,F-Kovacevic,S Cannes 1989 (1-0,
25)} 21... Qd8 22. d6 $6 Nd5 23. Qb3 (23. Qa3 Qb6+) 23... Nxf4 24. Rxf4 Qxd6
25. Qxf7+ Kh8 26. Rc7 Be5 $17 *

