1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 Bg7 8. Bb5+ {
This is a more refined display of aggressiveness than the hurried 8.e5. Since
the desirable 8...Bd7 and 8...Nbd7 run into 9.e5, Black's best is the
counter-developing} Nfd7 {The bishop is obviously exposed on b5, but White's
draft idea is that he will waste a tempo on retreating it to d3 while
returning with the knight to f6 would suppose throwing away two tempi. But the
practice has shown that Black is flexible enough to meet this plan. First of
all, White usually tries preventing ...Bg4, freeing Black's play. This mostly
happens when Black plays ...Nb6 or ...Nf6 with gain of time.} 9. Nf3 {White
allows the queenside expansion, heading for rapid development and an attack
based on f4-f5.} (9. Bd3 O-O 10. Nf3 {is another popular variation. White
"loses" his tempo at once in order to avoid Black's queenside play.} Qa5 $5 {
I find this very rare move quite interesting. Black threatens to win at least
a piece with ...Bxc3+ and more or less prevents White from immediately
castling. This way Black makes use of the fact that White helped with the
opening of the long diagonal.} ({The main line goes} 10... Na6 11. O-O Nc7 12.
a4 a6) 11. Bd2 ({The point is that} 11. O-O {runs into} c4 12. Bc2 b5 {
yielding Black queenside play much easier than usual.}) ({Or if} 11. Be3 Bxc3+
12. bxc3 Qxc3+ 13. Kf2 f5 14. exf5 Nf6 {White has problems on light squares
and no time to think of an attack along the dark long diagonal.}) 11... Re8 12.
Qe2 (12. Be2 c4 13. Bxc4 b5) 12... Qb6 $146 {This is a safer way of using the
favorable moment. Castling is absolutely impossible and b2 is hanging.} (12...
Na6 {is may lead to very interesting play.} 13. O-O Nb4 14. Bc4 (14. Bb1 b6 {
planning ...Ba6.}) 14... Nc2 15. Nb5 Qb6 16. Rad1 $5 $146 {This seems to be
strongest. The reason why the rook stands best on d1 will become clear later.}
(16. a4 Nxa1 17. a5 Qd8 18. Rxa1 Nf6 19. e5 dxe5 20. fxe5 {Salvermoser,B (2306)
-Handke,F (2504) Bad Wiessee 2002 (0-1, 31)} a6 $1 $146 21. Nd6 Qxd6 22. exd6
Rxe2 23. Bxe2 Bf5 $17) (16. Ba5 Qxa5 17. Qxc2 Bf8 {followed by ...a7-a6 is
comfortable for Black.}) 16... Nd4 ({The point is that} 16... a6 $2 {runs into}
