1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 Bg7 8. Bb5+
Nfd7 9. a4 {This avoids losing time early in the opening and prevents the
queenside expansion but weakens the b4-square, whereto the knight will be
heading soon.} O-O 10. Nf3 Na6 11. O-O Nb4 {The bishop's retreat to d3 has
been avoided and White has to permanently defend c2 in order to avoid ...
Nc2-d4.} 12. Re1 {The main move, but there are many alternatives with similar
evaluation.} (12. Be3 {This exposes the bishop not only to ...Ng4 but also
along the e-file.} Nf6 ({If} 12... a6 13. Be2 Re8 {White maintains his
flexibility with} 14. Bf2 Nf6 15. Nd2) 13. h3 Nxe4 {Black has to use the
favorable moment in order to prevent White from consolidating.} ({Now that
there is no danger of ...Nb6 followed by ...Bg4,} 13... a6 {runs into} 14. Bc4)
14. Nxe4 Qe7 {Blck retrieves the piece but the play remains interesting. He
needs being careful to prevent White from maintaining the initiative.} 15. Bxc5
(15. Ne5 {Ajrapetjan,Y (2389)-Golovlev,N (2306) Alushta 2007 (1-0, 43)} b6 16.
a5 Rb8) 15... dxc5 16. Re1 Bf5 17. d6 Qd8 18. Bc4 (18. Qd2 a6 19. Bc4 b5 20.
