1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f4 Bg7 8. Nf3 {
The classical treatment of the Three pawn attack. White develops naturally,
relying on his space advantage.} O-O 9. Be2 Nbd7 $5 {The safest continuation,
taking measures against the central break.} (9... Re8 {leads to unclear
complications after} 10. e5 dxe5 11. fxe5 Ng4 12. Bg5) 10. O-O ({The point is
that after} 10. e5 Ne8 $1 {White does not have favorable ways of keeping the
tension.} 11. e6 (11. O-O dxe5 12. fxe5 Nxe5 {followed by ...Nd6 blocking the
pawn.}) (11. exd6 Nxd6) 11... fxe6 12. dxe6 (12. Ng5 Nb6) 12... Nb6 13. O-O
Bxe6 {with little or no compensation for the pawn.}) 10... Re8 {Now that e5 is
under firm control this is well-timed, even though it means after White's
answer Black will not be able to plat the plan based on ...Na6.} 11. Nd2 (11.
e5 dxe5 12. fxe5 Nxe5 {is absolutely safe for Black.}) (11. Qc2 {exposes the
queen to a potential pin along the c-file after} Qc7 12. Kh1 c4 13. a4 a6 14.
Nd2 Nc5 15. Bxc4 Ncxe4 16. Ncxe4 Nxe4 17. Nxe4 Bf5 18. Re1 Rac8 {retrieving
the piece with obvious advantage.} 19. Bd3 Qxc2 20. Bxc2 Bxe4 (20... Rxc2 $2
21. Nf6+ Bxf6 22. Rxe8+ Kg7 23. h3 $13) 21. Rxe4 Rxe4 22. Bxe4 Re8 $17) 11...
Nb6 $5 {A very original plan, which enjoyed some popularity lately. Black
solves the conflict between his minor pieces at the cost of weakening his
queenside structure (see the next move). From b6, the knight sustains ...c5-c4
leaving the diagonal and the d7-square available for the bishop.} ({Decades
ago, another popular move used to be} 11... c4 12. Kh1 Nc5 13. e5 dxe5 14. fxe5
Rxe5 15. Nxc4 Re8 {but this is a bit o the edge for Black.}) 12. a4 (12. Re1 {
is a bit too slow.} Bh6 13. g3 Bh3 14. b3 $6 ({It was not too late for
harassing the knight:} 14. a4 a5 15. Bb5 Rf8 16. Nf3 $13) 14... Bg7 15. Rb1 Qc8
(15... Ng4 $5 16. Bxg4 Bxg4 17. Qxg4 Bxc3 {[%cal Gb6d5]} 18. Re2 Qf6 $17) 16.
Nc4 $2 {A surprising mistake for a corespondence game.} (16. Qc2 Ng4 $15) 16...
Nxc4 17. bxc4 (17. Bxc4 Ng4 18. Nb5 Qd7 19. Bb2 a6 $17 20. Bxg7 $2 axb5 $19)
17... Nxe4 $19 {Miettinen,R-Kaasalainen,A/FIN-ch fin corr 1966/Corr Nr. 1 (1/2,
34)}) 12... a5 {This is smaller concession than it may seem. With his knights
tied up to the defense of the central pawn, White cannot establish a firm
blockade on c4 and b5. Black can prepare ...Ng4 with ...h7-h5 (sometimes the
knight jump could follow even after h2-h3 or else play ...c5-c4.} 13. h3 {
White takes the g4-square under control in order to free the queen from this
task.} (13. Bb5 {would not have offered anything special:} Bd7 (13... Ng4 14.
Nf3 Bd7) 14. Bxd7 Qxd7 15. Qb3 Ra6 {The bishop exchange not only speeded up
Black's development, but also made this square available for the rook,
increasing Black's queenside stability.} 16. h3 c4 $132) (13. Kh1 Bd7 14. Ra3 (
14. h3 h5 15. Bd3 {Mihajlov,S (2076)-Tari,A (2295) Maribor 2012 (1/2, 20)} h4 {
/\...Nh5} 16. Be2 Rc8 17. Bf3 Nh7 {followed by ...f7-f5.}) (14. Bf3 h5 {
/\...Ng4} 15. h3 Ng4 $1 {preparing ...f7-f5 (possibly after ...Nh6)} 16. hxg4
$2 Qh4+ 17. Kg1 Bd4+) 14... Rc8 15. f5 Qe7 (15... gxf5 16. exf5 c4 {planning ..
.Rc5 leaves White in some sort of Zugzwang!}) 16. Bd3 gxf5 17. exf5 Nbxd5 18.
Nxd5 Nxd5 19. Ne4 Nf6 20. Bg5 Bc6 $15 {Naumkin,I (2443)-Iturrizaga,E (2642)
Benasque 2013 (0-1, 46)}) (13. Bf3 Bd7 14. Ndb1 h5 15. Na3 Ng4 $5 16. Nab5 f5
17. h3 fxe4 18. Nxe4 Bxb5 19. axb5 Bd4+ 20. Kh1 Nh6 21. Re1 Nf5 22. Kh2 {
½-½ Junge,W (2357)-Rihtaric,I (2071) ICCF email 2010}) 13... h5 {his
standard move somewhat weakens the kingside. With the knights relatively far
from e5, Black should permanently count with f4-f5.} (13... c4 $5 {is a worthy
alternative:} 14. Bf3 Nfd7 15. Nb5 Nc5 16. Qc2 f5 17. e5 dxe5 18. fxe5 Nd3 19.
Nxc4 Nxc4 20. Qxd3 Nxe5 $17 {Savina,A (2304)-Reyhan,D (2361) Konya 2012 (1/2,
54)}) 14. Qe1 {The start of an unfortunate maneuver.} (14. Bb5 {would be as
ineffective as on the previous move.} Bd7 15. Bxd7 Nfxd7 {Since ...Ng4 is not
available anymore, this is the logical capture now.} 16. Nb5 Nf6 {The knight
