17. Qf3 Qd7 {[%cal Gb6a4]} 18. Nc3 h4 19. f5 Nh5 $132) ({A possibly more
flexible plan than in the game would have been} 14. Re1 Bd7 (14... h4 15. Qc2
Bd7 16. Ra3 {with complex play. Black has to be careful, as pseudo-active play
may hand in the initiative to White:} Bh6 17. Nf3 Nh5 18. f5 Bxc1 19. Qxc1 $36
{with some kingside threats.}) 15. Bf3 Ng4 16. e5 Nh6 $15 {followed by ...Nf5.}
) 14... Bd7 15. Qg3 {Losing a pawn for almost nothing.} (15. Ra3 $5 {would
have been an alternative, although it would not be easy to indicate White's
next move.} Qe7 16. Rf2 Nh7) 15... Nfxd5 $1 16. exd5 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Rxe2 {
White not only has lost a pawn, but his structure has been seriously damaged.
His bishop will not be in time to create threats along the long diagonal.
Tregubov,P (2598)-Akopian,V (2675) Aix les Bains 2011 (0-1, 27)} *

