1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f3 {The same as
in the King's Indian, the Saemisch system looks very imposing. White builds up
a strong center as if asking Black to prove a constructive plan. But there is
a hidden drawback of this setup. As the KI expert Eduard Gufeld used to joke,
one should ask for the white king's knight's opinion about the whole thing!
Indeed, finding a good square for this piece requires time, as the most
natural move, Nf3, is denied. Optimally, the knight should land on f2, which
is the reason why Black should delay ...Nbd7 until the white knight has moved
to e2, so as to prevent Nh3.} Bg7 8. Bg5 ({Since after ...h7-h6, Be3 Black
usually includes ...h6-h5 in his plans,} 8. Be3 {will soon transpose. But in
certain cases, Black might find it simpler without the pressure on h6. The
play would continue with, for instance} O-O 9. Qd2 (9. Nge2 a6 10. a4 Nbd7)
9... a6 10. a4 Re8) 8... a6 ({With this move order Black avoids} 8... O-O 9.
Qd2 h6 10. Bxh6 Nxe4 {which is basically equal, but requires some additional
analysis in a position with a pawn down.} 11. Nxe4 Qh4+ 12. g3 Qxh6 13. Qxh6
Bxh6 14. Nxd6 Nd7) 9. a4 h6 10. Be3 (10. Bf4 {only exposes the bishop,
allowing Black gaining a tempo for his counterplay.} O-O 11. Qd2 Nh5 12. Be3 f5
13. Nge2 Qh4+ 14. g3 (14. Bf2 Qg5 $11) {½-½ Drozdovskij,Y (2462)-Kislinsky,A
(2412) Evpatoria 2001} 14... Nxg3 $1 15. Nxg3 f4 16. Bf2 fxg3 17. Bxg3 Qe7 18.
Bg2 Nd7 $15) ({The same applies to} 10. Bh4 O-O 11. Nge2 Nbd7 {Because of the
bishop's exposure, Ng3 is not possible now.} 12. Nc1 {Fedorowicz,J (2545)
-Watson,J (2395) San Francisco 1995 (1-0, 18)} Ne5 13. Be2 g5 14. Bf2 Nh5 $15)
10... O-O 11. Nge2 ({The main line, continuing} 11. Qd2 {is examined in lines
10 and 11.}) 11... Nbd7 {Now that Nh3 is not an issue anymore, Black can
develop his knight.} 12. Ng3 {The most popular move.} (12. Nc1 Ne5 (12... Nh5
$5 {is also interesting.} 13. g4 $6 {Valencia,B (2283)-Bitan,B (2320) Edmonton
2016 (0-1, 32)} Qh4+ 14. Bf2 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 Qf6 16. Kd2 Nf4 $15 {with a safe
blockade on dark squares.}) 13. Be2 Nh7 14. O-O (14. f4 Ng4 15. Bxg4 Qh4+ 16.
Bf2 Qxg4 17. Qxg4 Bxg4 18. O-O Rfe8 $15 {Geselschap, J-Piket, M (2355)
Eindhoven 1989 (½-½, 43)}) 14... f5 15. Qd2 g5 16. exf5 Bxf5 17. a5 Qe7 18.
Ra3 Rae8 $15 {with perfect regrouping for Black, Ehlvest, J (2485)-Mortensen,
E (2440) Leningrad 1984 (½-½, 22)}) 12... h5 {Immediately starting to chase
the enemy knight, before the h1-square becomes available for regrouping with
Nh1-f2.} 13. Be2 (13. h4 Ne5 14. Be2 Bd7 {leaves the e5-knight stable in view
of the weakness of the g4-square, while the h4-pawn causes White problems with
castling short.}) (13. Bg5 {practically transposes to line 12 with a tempo
less.} Qa5 14. Qd2 (14. Be2 Nh7) 14... b5 (14... Nh7 15. Be7) 15. Be2 c4 16.
O-O (16. Nd1 Qxd2+ 17. Bxd2 Rb8 18. Bb4 Nc5 19. Bxc5 dxc5 $17) 16... b4 17. Na2
Rb8 18. Be3 h4 19. Nh1 Qxa4 $15 {Muir,A (2367)-Jones,G (2567) Heraklio 2007 
(0-1, 23)}) 13... h4 14. Nf1 Rb8 $5 {This flexible, and in my opinion, the
best move has been played only once. Black makes a generally useful move (in
the long run ...b7-b5 will be possible) waiting for Nd2 to play the most
active knight move ...Nh5.} ({The main line goes} 14... Nh7 15. Nd2 f5 16. exf5
gxf5 {but things are not that clear for Black:} 17. O-O f4 18. Bf2 {True, he
has stability on dark squares, but White also has the light squares and a good
regrouping. The kingside weaknesses may later tell.}) (14... Nh5 $6 {is
premature due to} 15. g4 {as g3 is defended by the f1-knight.}) (14... Re8 {
is only second best.} 15. Nd2 ({The main problem is} 15. Bg5 {, compare with
the main line. I find ... Rb8 more useful than ...Re8.}) 15... Nh5 16. Nc4 Ne5
17. Qd2 Nxc4 18. Bxc4 f5 {1/2-1/2 (49) Dao,T (2565)-Smirin,I (2640) Las Palmas
1993}) 15. Bg5 (15. Nd2 Nh5 $1 16. Nc4 (16. f4 $2 Bd4 $1 {and the f4-pawn is
hanging.}) 16... Ne5 17. Nxe5 (17. O-O Nxc4 18. Bxc4 f5 19. exf5 Bxf5 $11)
17... Bxe5 18. Qd2 f5 19. Bg5 Bf6 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 $15) (15. g4 Nh7 16. Nd2 Bd4
17. Bh6 Re8 18. Nc4 Qf6 19. Bc1 b5 $17 {Pitkaenen,J (2437)-Le Page,C (2361)
ICCF email 2010 (27, 0-1)}) (15. Qc2 Ne5) 15... h3 {Black plays on both wings.
He prepares ...b7-b5 by weakening f3!!} 16. gxh3 {This looks like a concession,
but it is the only move fighting against ...Ne5 by controlling g4 and allowing
f3-f4. Against other moves ...b7-b5 remains possible, but it is better to
prepare it by centralizing the knight.} (16. g3 Ne5 17. Ne3 (17. f4 Neg4 18.
Qc2 Qe8 $17 {Attacking e4 and preparing ...b7-b5.}) (17. Nd2 Qe8) 17... Qe8
$132 18. f4 $2 Neg4 19. Nxg4 Nxg4 20. Bf3 (20. Bxg4 Bxc3+ 21. bxc3 Qxe4+ 22.
Kd2 Bxg4 23. Qxg4 Qxd5+ 24. Kc2 Qg2+ 25. Kb3 b5 26. Rhb1 b4 27. c4 Qe4 $19)
20... Bd4 21. Qe2 f6 22. Bh4 f5 23. Bxg4 fxg4 $19) (16. g4 Ne5 17. Nd2 (17. f4
Nexg4 18. Bxg4 Bxg4 19. Bxf6 Bxd1 $17) (17. Ne3 b5 18. axb5 axb5 19. Bxb5 c4
20. O-O Qc7 21. Kh1 Qc5 22. Bc6 Nh7 23. Na4 Qa7 24. Bf4 Nd3 $17) 17... Bd7 {
There is no way to trap the central knight.} 18. a5 (18. Bxf6 Qxf6 {prevents
f3-f4 anyway.}) (18. f4 Nexg4 19. Bxg4 Bxg4 20. Bxf6 Qd7 $1 21. Bxg7 Bxd1 22.
Bxf8 Bh5 23. Bh6 Qg4 24. Kf2 Qh4+ 25. Ke3 Qf6 26. Nb3 Qd8 27. Nd2 f6 $17 {
The h6-bishop is doomed.}) 18... b5 19. axb6 Qxb6 20. Ra2 Bb5 {with at least
equal play.}) 16... b5 $1 ({Black cannot prepare this with} 16... Ne5 {due to}
17. f4 $16) 17. axb5 axb5 18. Nxb5 (18. Bxb5 c4 $1 $132) 18... Ne5 {Black has
strong pressure on practically the whole board, compensating for the missing
pawns.} 19. Nd2 (19. f4 Nf3+ $1 20. Bxf3 Rxb5 $15) 19... Qd7 20. f4 (20. Qa4
Qxh3 $19) (20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. f4 Bh4+ 22. Kf1 Qxh3+ 23. Kg1 Qe3+ 24. Kf1 Bh3#)
20... Nh7 $1 21. Bh4 (21. h4 Rxb5 22. Bxb5 Qxb5 23. fxe5 Nxg5 24. hxg5 Qxb2 25.
O-O Qxe5 $15) 21... Qxh3 22. Bg3 Qg2 23. Rf1 {Black has a strong attack,
yielding him at least equal chances.} Rxb5 (23... Ng4 $5 24. Bf3 Qh3 25. Qe2
Rxb5 26. Qxb5 Nxh2 $44) 24. Bxb5 Bg4 25. Qc2 c4 26. Bxc4 Nxc4 27. Qxc4 Re8 $11
{Sooner or later White will need forcing a draw by perpetual with the mechanism
} 28. Rf2 Qh1+ 29. Rf1 Qg2 30. Rf2 *

