1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f3 Bg7 8. Bg5 a6
9. a4 h6 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qd2 {This is the main move and rightly so. The latent
pressure on h6 slightly restricts Black's possibilities.} Re8 12. Nge2 (12. Be2
{is the start of a wait and see game, hoping that Black will exhaust his
useful moves and will play ...Nbd7, allowing Nh3. But this does not work.} h5
$1 13. a5 (13. Bd1 Nbd7 14. Nge2 Ne5 15. b3 Bd7 16. a5 h4 $5 $146 17. O-O h3
18. g3 Nh7 $132) 13... b5 (13... Nh7 14. Bd1 Nd7 15. Nge2 Ne5 16. b3 Qh4+ 17.
Bf2 Qf6 18. Qe3 h4 $36) 14. axb6 Qxb6 15. Bd1 (15. Ra2 a5 {/\...Na6-b4}) 15...
Nbd7 16. Nge2 (16. Nh3 Ne5) 16... Ne5 17. b3 a5 $1 $10 {The position remains
complicated but it is obvious that Black has his own play, the basic idea in
the Benoni!} 18. O-O Ba6 19. Bc2 Qc7 $1 {Unpinning the pawn in order to
prepare ...c5-c4.} 20. Ra4 (20. h3 c4 21. f4 Nd3 22. bxc4 Nb2 $13) (20. Rfc1
Nfd7 21. Kh1 c4 22. Bd4 Nc5 23. bxc4 Nxc4 24. Qg5 Ne5 25. f4 Ned3 26. Bxg7 Kxg7
27. Ng3 Nf2+ 28. Kg1 Qa7 $1 {After the game my opponent called this move
"nice!".} 29. Nxh5+ Kg8 30. Nf6+ Kg7 31. Nh5+ Kg8 32. Nf6+ {½-½ Christiansen,
L (2575)-Marin,M (2475) Szirak 1987}) 20... Nfd7 21. Rfa1 Bxe2 $1 22. Nxe2 (22.
Qxe2 $6 Nxf3+ $17) 22... Nb6 $1 23. R4a2 (23. Rxa5 $2 Nxf3+ $1 24. gxf3 Bxa1
$19) 23... a4 24. Nc3 (24. bxa4 Nec4 25. Qd3 Nxe3 26. Qxe3 Bxa1 27. Rxa1 Nxd5
$19) 24... Qb7 $5 25. Bf2 (25. bxa4 $2 Nec4 26. Qe1 Nxe3 $19 27. Qxe3 $2 Bd4) (
25. Nxa4 $2 Nxa4 26. Rxa4 Nxf3+ 27. gxf3 Bxa1 $19) 25... axb3 26. Bxb3 (26.
Rxa8 Rxa8 27. Rxa8+ Qxa8 28. Bxb3 Qa3 $36) 26... Rxa2 27. Bxa2 (27. Qxa2 Nxf3+
$17) (27. Rxa2 Nbc4) 27... Qa6 28. Rb1 Ra8 $17 {Genov-Marin, Solsona 2004. 
(0-1, 34)}) 12... Nbd7 13. Ng3 {A familiar move. But with the queen on d2
White will find it harder to regroup with his knight than in Line 9.} ({
White can reach the optimal regrouping with a loss of two tempi with respect
to Nh3-f2 with:} 13. Nd1 Ne5 14. Nec3 {But this offers Black the needed time
to start a kingside pawn attack.} g5 15. Be2 (15. h4 g4 16. Bxh6 Bxh6 17. Qxh6
gxf3 18. Ne3 f2+ 19. Kd2 Nfg4 20. Nxg4 Bxg4 21. Be2 f5 $132) 15... Nh5 16. O-O
(16. g4 {Hlavacek,R-Hybl,V Czech Republic 1999 (½-½, 28)} Nf4 $1 17. Bxf4
gxf4 18. Qxf4 Ng6 19. Qe3 Bd7 20. a5 h5 $15 {WHite is imperfectly coordinated
and his dark squares are weak.}) 16... Qf6 17. a5 (17. Rb1 Nf4 18. b4 c4 19. a5
Bd7 20. Kh1 Rac8 $15 {Rajkovic-Nataf, Herceg Novi 2005}) 17... Nf4 18. Na4 Bd7
19. Ndc3 Bxa4 20. Rxa4 (20. Nxa4 Nxe2+ 21. Qxe2 Re7 22. Nb6 Rae8 23. Rab1 Qg6
24. Qc2 f5 25. exf5 Qh5 $15 26. Bf2 $2 g4 27. f4 Nf3+ 28. gxf3 Re2 29. Qd3 gxf3
$19) 20... Rac8 21. Kh1 {Dreev-Kasparov, Moscow (rapid) 1996 (0-1, 29)} h5 22.
Bc4 h4 $132) (13. Bxh6 {leads to simplifications and a probable draw.} Nxe4 14.
Nxe4 Qh4+ 15. g3 Qxh6 16. Qxh6 Bxh6 17. Nxd6 Re3 18. f4 (18. Bh3 Nb6 19. Nxc8
Nxc8 20. Kf2 Nd6 $44) 18... Nb6 19. Kd2 (19. Bg2 $2 Bg4 $19) (19. Nxc8 Rxc8 20.
Bg2 $2 Rce8 $19) 19... Nxd5 20. Nc3 (20. Bg2 Bg4 21. Nc3 {Benedetto,G (2139)
-Markic,V ICCF email 2000 (1-0, 30)} Re6 22. Nxf7 Kxf7 23. Bxd5 Rd8 24. Kc2
Rxd5 25. Nxd5 Re2+ 26. Kc1 Bf5 $44 {with obvious compensation for the material.
The bishops are dominating completely.}) 20... Re6 21. Nxc8 Nxc3 22. bxc3 Rxc8
$11 {Dreev,A (2670)-Kasparov,G (2775) Moscow 1996 (0-1, 82). It is interesting
that Kasparov entered this line in a moment when he needed to win in order to
level the square and not be eliminated.}) (13. Nc1 {[%emt 0:00:11] is examined
in Line}) 13... h5 {Not a new idea to us.} 14. Be2 (14. Bg5 {does not prevent}
h4 {at all.} 15. Nge2 (15. Bxh4 Nxe4 $1 $15) 15... h3 16. g4 Ne5 17. Ng1 {
White's troubles are obvious.} Qa5 18. Be2 Qb4 19. Nd1 (19. Nxh3 Nxf3+ 20. Bxf3
Nxe4 21. Nxe4 Rxe4+ $15 22. Bxe4 $2 Qxe4+ $19) 19... Nxf3+ 20. Nxf3 Qxe4 21.
Ra3 Bxg4 22. Nf2 Qxf3 23. Rxf3 Bxf3 24. O-O Bxe2 $19 {Botsari,A (2309)
-Vuckovic,B (2433) Chania 1999 (0-1, 32)}) 14... h4 15. Nf1 Nh7 {Preparing the
usual counterplay with ..f7-f5.} 16. Bf2 (16. Qc1 f5 17. Nd2 Bd4 18. Nc4 {
Wang Yue-Shchekachev, Bad Zwesten 2003} Ne5 $15) (16. g4 Ne5 17. h3 g5 18. Nh2
Ng6 19. Bd3 Be5 20. Ne2 Qf6 21. Ra2 Bg3+ 22. Kd1 Bd7 23. a5 Ne5 $19 {with a
dream blockade in Middelveld,M (2102)-Van den Doel,E (2591) Leiden 2010 (0-1,
67)}) 16... Ne5 17. Ne3 Qg5 $132 {Black has achieved comfortable development
and is ready for starting his counterplay.} 18. O-O f5 19. Kh1 f4 20. Nc4 Nxc4
21. Bxc4 Be5 22. Qe1 (22. h3 $5 Nf6 23. Kh2 Nh5 24. a5 Bd7 25. Na4 Bxa4 26.
Rxa4 Ng3 27. Re1 {White rightly thought that after the inevitable opening of
the queenside his king would feel uncomfortable, but in the game, the king got
into trouble straight under the kingside attack!}) 22... Qh6 23. Bxh4 (23. h3
$5) 23... g5 24. Bf2 Nf6 25. g3 Kf7 $40 26. h4 $2 {Novikov,I (2280)-Loginov,V 
(2395) Volgodonsk 1983 (0-1, 44)} g4 $19 *

