1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. f3 Bg7 8. Bg5 a6
9. a4 h6 10. Be3 O-O 11. Qd2 Re8 12. Nge2 Nbd7 13. Nc1 {This is more populr
than 13.Ng3, but fails to impress. The knight has only one possible plan: N1a2
followed by b2-b4, but what next?} Ne5 14. Be2 (14. Bxh6 {is simply bad now.}
Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Qh4+ {The problem is that with the knight on e5} 16. g3 {is out
of question}) {But now Bxh6 is a threat already.} 14... h5 15. O-O (15. h3 Nh7
16. f4 Nd7 17. O-O (17. g4 $2 Bxc3 18. bxc3 Ndf6 $19 {Gaede,D (2193)-Schaefer,
M (2346) Travemuende 2005 (0-1, 26)}) 17... f5 $132) 15... Nh7 {Preparing as
usual ...f7-f5.} 16. Rb1 $5 {Preparing b2-b4. Other plans have been tried, too,
without any special success.} (16. Ra3 f5 17. N1a2 ({If} 17. h3 {Botsari,A 
(2362)-Cedikova,K (2263) Mallorca 2004 (0-1, 54) Black should not fear the
kingside expansion:} Nf6 $1 $11 {for if} 18. exf5 Bxf5 19. g4 Bd7 20. f4 $2 Nf7
$17 {and White is hanging, partly because of his passive knight on c1.}) 17...
Nf6 18. a5 fxe4 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. fxe4 {A dream position for Black, of course.}
Bg4 $5 21. h3 Bxe2 22. Qxe2 b5 23. axb6 Qxb6 $15 {Alterman-Gelfand, Riga 1987 
(0-1, 38)}) (16. N1a2 f5 17. b4 (17. Rfe1 $6 Bd7 18. exf5 Bxf5 $15 {
Brunner-Xie, Shanghai (m/1) 1995}) 17... cxb4 18. Nxb4 f4 $1 {Making use of
the exposed knight on b4.} 19. Bf2 (19. Bxf4 $2 Qb6+) 19... g5 20. a5 Qf6 21.
Na4 g4 22. Kh1 Ng5 $40 {Czerwonski-Cvitan, Katowice 1992 (0-1, 31)}) (16. f4 $6
Ng4 17. Bxg4 Bxg4 18. h3 (18. f5 Bxf5 $1 19. exf5 Rxe3 20. f6 Rxc3 21. bxc3
Nxf6 $17) 18... Bd7 19. N1e2 (19. e5 {Qendro,L (2338)-Cacciola,A (2114) Lugano
2013 (½-½, 23)} dxe5 20. Bxc5 Rc8 $15) 19... b5 $15) (16. h3 f5 17. f4 (17.
N1a2 Nf6) 17... Nf7 18. exf5 (18. e5 dxe5 19. Bxc5 b6 20. Be3 Bb7 21. N1a2 Nf6
22. Bc4 Nd6 23. Bb3 a5 $17 {With perfect blockade on dark squares, Lin,W (2440)
-Tan,Z (2464) Hefei 2010 (1-0, 43)}) 18... Bxf5 19. Bf2 Nf6 $15) 16... f5 17.
b4 c4 {Black keeps the queenside closed, ensuring himself thecontrol over d3,
where his minor pieces may eventually land and restricts the enemy knight at
the same time.} 18. N1a2 (18. f4 Ng4 (18... Nf7 19. Bd4 Nf6 {is also good,
Hobaica,J (2405)-Barbosa,E (2365) Brasilia 2010 (½-½ , 45)}) 19. Bxg4 hxg4
20. N1e2 Nf6 $15) ({If} 18. b5 {the simplest is} a5 {preventing White's
counterplay.}) 18... Nf6 19. h3 $5 (19. b5 fxe4 20. fxe4 Bg4 {ensures Black
the invasion on d3.}) 19... Bd7 ({Actually the approach in an older game is
simpler and more effective:} 19... fxe4 $5 20. Nxe4 $1 Nxe4 21. fxe4 b5 22. Nc3
Bd7 $17 {Campos Moreno-Martin Gonzalez, Barcelona 1986 (0-1, 33)}) 20. a5 Qe7
21. Rbe1 (21. Bg5 Nf7 22. Bxc4 Nxg5 23. Qxg5 Rac8 24. Bb3 Nxe4 25. Nxe4 fxe4
26. Qxg6 e3 27. Bc2 e2 28. Rfe1 Qe3+ 29. Kh1 Qd2 30. Rbc1 Re3 $5 $19) 21...
Rac8 $15 {Erdos-Acs, Magyarorszag 2004 (0-1, 32)} *

