1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Bd3 Bg7 8. Nge2
{This (then still rare) line came into the limelight after Penrose defeated
Tal with it (see the strategic article The Central Break).} O-O 9. O-O a6 10.
a4 ({Black faces no problems after} 10. Bg5 b5 11. Qd2 Re8 12. a3 Nbd7) 10...
Nbd7 11. h3 ({Once again, developing the bishop to g5 instead of e3 does not
contribute to White's harmony. The bishop will be exposed after f2-f4 and the
dark squares left behind will become vulnerable.} 11. Bg5 Qc7 12. b3 ({Trying
to prevent ...c5-c4 for if} 12. Qd2 c4 13. Bc2 Nc5 14. Nd4 Ng4 {Black's
position surely is more active than in the min line.}) 12... Ne5 13. Bc2 Nh5 $5
$146 {Preparing ...f7-f5.} 14. f4 Ng4 15. Qd2 c4 {With strong Blck counterplay.
}) 11... Re8 12. Ng3 (12. f4 {may just transpose but White does not get
anything by hurrying up with e4-e5.} c4 13. Bc2 Nc5 14. Ng3 Rb8 15. e5 dxe5 16.
fxe5 ({White is not in time to establish the blockade on e4 after} 16. f5 e4)
16... Rxe5 17. Bf4 Nfd7 18. Nge2 Re8 19. Bxb8 Nxb8 {The g7-bishop is strong
and Black has the plan ...Nb8-d7-e5-d3.}) (12. b3 $146 {fails to prevent
Black's queenside counterplay.} Rb8 13. Be3 Ne5 14. Bc2 b5 $15) 12... Qc7 13.
f4 ({Once again} 13. Bg5 {needs brief mentioning.} c4 14. Bc2 Rb8 15. a5 b5 16.
axb6 Nxb6 17. Qd2 Nfd7 18. Ra2 Nc5 {Shtyrenkov,V (2514)-Kononenko,D (2449)
Alushta 2003 (½-½, 50) It is not hard to see that the bishop would have been
more useful on e3.}) (13. Be3 {is a tricky move order.} Rb8 ({Since White has
not weakened the g1-a7 diagonal Black is more exposed after the hurried} 13...
c4 14. Bc2 Rb8 15. a5 {for instance} Nc5 16. Qe2 b5 17. axb6 Rxb6 18. Bxc5 {
Since 18...Qxc5 does not check, thus running into 19.Na4, Black is forced to
the disgusting} dxc5 $16) 14. Qe2 (14. f4 c4 {transposes to the main line.})
14... h5 {Since the queenside play is temporarily stuck, Black, opens a new
front, taking advantage of the exposed position of the white queen.} 15. f4 h4
16. Nh1 c4 17. Bc2 b5 $11 {Milanovic,D (2429)-Velickovic,S (2399) Budva 2003 
(1-0, 27)}) 13... c4 14. Bc2 Rb8 15. Be3 Nc5 ({The slightly premature} 15... b5
16. axb5 axb5 {allows} 17. Ra7 {when the hanging b5-pan forces} Qd8 $14) 16.
Bd4 ({Another possible move order is} 16. Qf3 b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. e5 dxe5 19.
fxe5 Rxe5 20. Bd4 {transposing.}) (16. a5 {may lead to interesting play:} b5
17. axb6 Rxb6 18. Na4 {Basically winning an exchange, bu with adequate black
compensation.} Nxa4 19. Bxa4 Re7 20. Bxb6 Qxb6+ 21. Kh2 h5 (21... Nxe4 22. Re1
$14) 22. e5 (22. Bc2 h4 23. Ne2 Nxe4 {looks perfect for Black.}) 22... dxe5 23.
d6 Re6 24. d7 Nxd7 25. f5 Rd6 26. Qc2 Nc5 27. Be8 (27. Qxc4 Rd4 28. Qc2 h4 29.
Ne2 Bxf5 30. Rxf5 Rxa4 31. Rxa4 Nxa4 32. Rf1 Nc5 33. Qc4 Ne6 34. Qxh4 Qxb2 35.
Qe4 Qb6 36. Qd5 Bf8 $11) (27. fxg6 Rxg6 28. Nxh5 Bb7 29. g3 Qe6 30. Rad1 Nd3
31. b3 Bc8 32. Qg2 Rh6 33. bxc4 e4 34. g4 Be5+ 35. Kh1 Qxc4 $44) 27... Bb7 28.
fxg6 fxg6 29. Rad1 e4 30. Qxc4+ Kh8 31. Qf7 Nd3 32. Qe7 Re6 33. Rf8+ Kh7 34.
Qf7 h4 35. Nf5 gxf5 36. Qxf5+ Rg6 37. Qh5+ Rh6 38. Qf5+ Rg6 39. Qh5+ {½-½
Westera, B (2432)-Kazoks, A (2412) ICCF email 2012 Entertaining until the very
end.}) (16. e5 $6 {is an imprecise move order:} dxe5 17. fxe5 Rxe5 18. Bd4 {
Black is not forced to transpose to the main line ith ...b7-b5 but can play}
Bxh3 $1 $17 19. gxh3 $2 Rg5 $19) 16... b5 17. axb5 axb5 18. e5 {White cannot
delay concrete action anymore.} (18. f5 {offers some attacking chances, but
with the white knights far from the e5-square things are not threatening for
Blck.} Qe7 $5 $146 ({If} 18... Nfd7 19. f6 Bf8 {it remains an open question
whether the bishop will be ever able to move again. Computers think Black is
better but I would be afraid of being completely lost.}) (18... g5 {is the
most popular move, but I am reluctant to such weakening moves without need.})
19. Qf3 Ncd7 20. Qf2 Ne5 21. Ra7 Bd7 22. Rfa1 h5 $5 $132) (18. Qf3 $2 {loses
material to} Nfxe4 19. Bxg7 Nxg3) 18... dxe5 19. fxe5 Rxe5 20. Qf3 {It is
useful to maintain the tension yet.} (20. Bxe5 Qxe5 21. Qf3 Bb7 {offers Black
a great position.}) 20... Rg5 21. Nge2 Nh5 (21... Nd3 $5 {was played only in
one correspondence game but is worth investigating.} 22. Bxd3 cxd3 23. Qxd3 {
MacLeod,D-Masurel,J corr 1990 (½-½, 37)} Bf5 24. Qd2 h6 $15) 22. Bxg7 Kxg7
23. d6 (23. g4 $6 {is at least risky.} Bxg4 $5 24. hxg4 f5 25. d6 Qxd6 26. Rfd1
Rxg4+ {Settling for a draw.} (26... Qf8 $5) 27. Qxg4 Qxd1+ 28. Rxd1 fxg4 29.
Rd5 Na4 30. Bxa4 bxa4 31. Nxa4 Rb4 32. Ra5 Nf6 33. Nec3 h5 34. Rb5 {½-½
Hechler,G-Altrock,R Germany 1995}) 23... Qxd6 24. Qxf7+ Kh6 {The position is
balanced, with both kings in similar degree of trouble!} 25. Rad1 Nd3 $1 ({
A novelty over a game I had in my repertoire:} 25... Qe5 26. h4 $40 {Knaak,R 
(2495)-Enders,P (2315) German Dem Rep 1982 (1-0, 32)}) 26. Ne4 Qb6+ 27. Kh1 Rf5
28. Rxf5 Bxf5 29. Bxd3 cxd3 30. N2g3 Bxe4 31. Nxe4 Qd4 32. Nf2 Ng3+ $11 {
½-½ Vinot,S (2499)-Knebel,W (2449) ICCF email 2002} 33. Kh2 $2 Nf5 34. Nxd3
Rc8 *

