1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. e4 g6 7. Nge2 Bg7 8. Ng3
{This variation may arise via the King's Indian move order. White intends
developing in the spirit of the Samisch attack, but delays f2-f3 so as to gain
a tempo in the early stage. Concretely, White hopes to be in time to answer ...
h5-h4 with the most desirable regrouping Nh1-f2.} a6 $1 {Black has to start
his plan at once in order to prevent the aforementioned plan.} 9. a4 h5 10. Be2
{White has not enough development to deviate from the natural course.} (10. Bg5
h4 {forces the knight retreating to the previous position, while the advance
of the h-pawn is useful for Black (meaning he got two extra tempi).} 11. Nge2
Nbd7 12. Qd2 Qa5 13. Nc1 {The knight cannot find another square for regrouping.
} h3 14. g3 Ne5 15. Be2 Bg4 {White will soon have problems on light squares.})
(10. Bd3 {leads to some sort of Penrose attack with premature Ng3 on the way.}
h4 11. Nge2 h3 12. g3 Nbd7 {and White will not be in time defending f3 and
avoiding the exchange on d3 at the same time.}) 10... Qe7 {Another important
move, attacking e4 and aiming at inducing f2-f3 in a moment when White cannot
cover the dark squares too well.} 11. Bg5 {The thematic move, played by one of
the greatest Saemisch experts.} (11. f3 Nh7 {prepares ...f7-f5 leaving White
short of constructive moves.} 12. Be3 (12. O-O $2 Bd4+ {forces} 13. Rf2 $17 {
in order to leave the h1-square available for the wandering knight.}) (12. Nf1
O-O 13. Ne3 Nd7 14. O-O f5 15. exf5 Bd4 16. Qd2 gxf5 17. Kh1 f4 18. Nc4 Ne5 {
Black has achieved stability on dark squares and White still has to regroup
before completing his development. This compensates for the kingside
weaknesses.}) 12... h4 13. Nf1 Nd7 14. Nd2 f5 15. Nc4 O-O {Threatening
'''f5-f4.} 16. exf5 Ne5 17. Nxe5 (17. Nb6 Bxf5 $1 18. Nxa8 Nxf3+ 19. gxf3 Qxe3
{[%cal Gh7g5]} 20. Qd2 Qxd2+ 21. Kxd2 Bh6+ 22. Kd1 Rxa8 $44) 17... Qxe5 18.
fxg6 Qxe3 19. gxh7+ Kh8 $44) (11. Qc2 {Defends e4 but places the queen on a
non-typical square for this system.} Nh7 (11... h4 12. Nf1 Nh5 $6 13. g4 hxg3
14. hxg3 $16 {Perdomo,L (2361)-Rodi,L (2340) Sao Paulo 2008 (½-½, 39)}) 12.
Nf1 (12. O-O O-O {leaves White short of constructive moves. f2-f3 is not
playable for known reasons and} 13. Be3 h4 14. Nh1 f5 {offers Black good
counterplay as the knight is still far from the center and the bishop is not
defended on e3.}) 12... Nd7 13. Be3 O-O 14. Nd2 Ne5 15. O-O f5 $11) (11. O-O {
simply loses the pawn without compensation.} h4 12. Nh1 h3 (12... Nxe4 {
is even simpler.} 13. Nxe4 Qxe4 14. Bf3 Qe7 15. Re1 Be5 $17 {White cannot take
advantage of the pin:} 16. Bg4 Bxg4 17. Qxg4 Kf8 18. f4 Bd4+) 13. g4 Nxe4 14.
Nxe4 Qxe4 15. Bf3 {Bianco,V (2141)-Colovic,A (2502) Bratto 2013 (0-1, 32)} Qe7
16. Re1 Be5 17. Ng3 {In the previous line the knight did not have this square.}
Nd7 18. Bh1 O-O $15 19. f4 $2 Bd4+ $19) 11... Qe5 12. Qd2 ({As usual, stopping
the h5-pawn weakens the kingside.} 12. h4 Nh7 13. Be3 O-O 14. Qd2 Re8 15. Bf4
Qe7 16. Nf1 Nd7 17. Ne3 Ne5 $11 {The knight is stable on e5 due to the
weakness of the g4-square and White will not find it simple castling short as
h4 is hanging.}) (12. f4 Qd4 $132) 12... h4 13. Bf4 $6 {This more or less
loses a pawn.} ({White should have embarked the following sharp line.} 13. f4
Qd4 14. Nf1 h3 15. g3 Ng4 16. Qxd4 (16. Bf3 f6 17. Bh4 O-O 18. Qe2 Qb4 19. Ra2
f5 $132) 16... Bxd4 17. Nd1 f6 18. Bh4 Rg8 {The bishop is doomed but White has
his own plan going on.} 19. Nd2 g5 20. Nc4 gxh4 21. Nb6 Nd7 22. Nxa8 Kd8 {
The position remains very complicated but Black has good compensation for the
exchange. The d4-bishop is dominating, there is strong kingside pressure and
the a8-knight has along way back home. Here is an illustrative line.} 23. a5 f5
24. Ra3 fxe4 25. gxh4 Ngf6 26. Rg3 Rh8 27. Nc3 Rxh4 28. Rf1 Rh8 29. Nb6 Nxb6
30. axb6 Bf5 31. Rg5 Bd7 32. Kd1 Be8 33. Kc2 Bf7 $13) 13... Qe7 14. Nf1 h3 (
14... Nxe4 $15 {is simpler.}) 15. Bf3 $2 (15. g3 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Qxe4 $15) 15...
hxg2 16. Bxg2 Bh3 $17 {Dreev,A (2688)-Minasian,A (2557) Moscow 2009 (0-1, 46)}
*

