1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 e6 4. Nc3 exd5 5. cxd5 d6 6. Nf3 g6 7. Bg5 {The
systems based on Bg5 and Nf3 used to be popular long time ago, but now they
are less topical. For space reasons I will cover them in lesser detail.} Bg7 8.
e3 ({Sightly more flexible, but also less aggressive than} 8. e4 a6 $1 ({
Black prepares two possible plans, which are not working with the pawn on a7:} 
8... h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 11. Bb5+ Kf8 {Forced as the d6-pwn is hanging.}
12. e5 $36) (8... Bg4 $2 {This is in the spirit of our ...Bg4 Classical system
published in database 1.} 9. Bb5+ $1 Nbd7 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 {Black landed
under an unpleasant double pin.} h6 12. Bxd7+ {forces} Kxd7 $16) 9. Nd2 ({If} 
9. a4 {Blck has a choice between the aforementioned plans. I recommend the
latter, as it more or less transposes to our repertoire gainst the classical
system. The former is not bad either, but there is no need to analyze
additional lines.}) 9... h6 10. Bh4 b5 {Black has gained queenside space and
the only open question remains whether White will find a way of stabilizing on
light squares after a later a2-a4.} 11. Be2 O-O 12. Qc2 Re8 13. O-O Nbd7 14. a4
(14. Rae1 c4 15. f4 Nc5 16. Kh1 Qc7 17. a3 Bd7 $15 {Hoi,C (2415)-Ostergaard,J 
(2290) Copenhagen 1993 (1-0, 38) White starts hanging in the center.}) 14... b4
15. Nd1 b3 $1 {This is a typical way of fighting against the blockade.} 16. Qb1
(16. Qxb3 g5 17. Bg3 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Rxe4 19. Qc2 Nf6 20. Ne3 Rb4 $5 $146 {
[%cal Gf6e4] /\...Ne4}) (16. Qd3 Rb8 17. f4 Rb4 18. Nc4 Qc7 19. Bf3 {Taimanov,
M-Boleslavsky,I Moscow 1960 (1-0, 31)} Nxe4 $3 20. Bxe4 Nb6 {If 21.Nxb6 Qxb6
the simultaneous threats ...c5-c4 and taking on e4 retrieve the piece keeping
an extra pawn and a positional advantage.} 21. Nde3 Bd4 22. Nxb6 Bxe3+ 23. Qxe3
Qxb6 $17) 16... g5 17. Bg3 Nxd5 {This is what happens if too many pieces step
back.} 18. Nc4 Nf4 19. Bxf4 gxf4 (19... d5 $5) 20. Nxd6 Re6 21. Nf5 {Material
is equal but the structure is unusual. Black's activity compensates for the
pawn weaknesses.} Qg5 22. h4 Qg6 23. Ra3 Rb8 24. f3 Bd4+ $1 25. Nxd4 cxd4 26.
Qd3 {Atakisi,F-Grigoryev,V ICCF email 2005 (½-½, 31)} Ne5 27. Qxd4 Qf6 28.
Qa7 Nc6 29. Qf2 Rd6 30. Bc4 Be6 31. Bxe6 fxe6 32. Nc3 Qd4 33. Raa1 Qxf2+ 34.
Rxf2 Ne5 $15 {The b2-pawn is likely to cause White problems soon.}) 8... h6 9.
Bh4 g5 {In the absence of the threat e4-e5, the check on b5 is not dangerous.}
({Therefore Black delays} 9... a6 10. a4 {, which might later allow White
establishing a blockade with Nc4. For instance:} g5 11. Bg3 Nh5 12. Nd2 Nxg3
13. hxg3 Nd7 14. Nce4 Nf6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Nc4 Rb8 17. a5 $14 {Bagirov,
V-Beliavsky, A Vitebsk 1970 (½-½, 41)}) 10. Bg3 Nh5 11. Bb5+ ({The
alternative is} 11. Qa4+ Kf8 12. Qc2 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Nd7 {The king is not in
danger on f8 and the rook is useful on h8 as it sustains the attack based on ..
. 5-h4.} 14. Be2 Qe7 15. O-O (15. Nd2 Ne5 16. e4 Bd7 17. Nf1 c4 18. a4 {
Najdorf, M (2510)-Cuasnicu,O (2410) Buenos Aires 1975 (1-0, 43)} h5 $15) 15...
h5 16. Ne4 (16. Qe4 {Zakhvatov,V (2360)-Grechihin,V (2490) Cherepovets 1997 
(0-1, 34)} h4 $15) 16... g4 17. Nh4 Ne5 $13) (11. Nd2 {is not dangerous
without the insertion of ...a7-a6 and a2-a4.} Nxg3 12. hxg3 Nd7 13. Nce4 (13.
Qc2 a6 14. a4 Ne5 15. Be2 O-O 16. f4 Ng4 17. Nc4 Re8 18. Bxg4 Bxg4 19. Ra3 gxf4
20. gxf4 Qf6 $15 {Polugaevsky,L-Bilek,I Ordzhonikidze 1964 (½-½, 32)}) 13...
Nf6 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $11 15. Nc4 $2 b5) 11... Kf8 {Same comment as after 11.Qa4+.
} 12. Bd3 (12. a4 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Na6 14. Nd2 Nb4 15. Bc4 a6 16. g4 Rb8 17. O-O
$2 h5 $17 {Ostrowski,L (2354)-Vasquez Schroder,R (2521) Dos Hermanas 2004 (0-1,
34)}) 12... Nxg3 13. hxg3 Nd7 14. Qc2 (14. Bf5 b5 $1 15. O-O (15. Nxb5 Qa5+ 16.
Nc3 Bxc3+ 17. bxc3 Qxc3+ 18. Kf1 Kg7 $15) 15... b4 16. Ne4 Nb6 17. Bxc8 Rxc8
18. Rb1 Qe7 $11 {Frias Pablaza,V (2440)-Vilela de Acuna,J (2440) Bayamo 1983 
(½-½, 42) White is not enough well coordinated to control the light squares
while the d5-pawn is hanging and the queenside majority remains very mobile.})
14... a6 {Finally.} 15. a4 b6 {A typical move, securing the queenside
flexibility.} (15... h5 $5 16. Bf5 Ne5 17. Nxe5 Bxe5 18. f4 gxf4 19. gxf4 Bg7
20. Kf2 Rh6 $132) 16. O-O Qe7 17. Bf5 Ne5 18. Bxc8 Rxc8 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Rae1
Rg8 ({ACtually it makes sense keeping the king's rook on the h-file.} 20... Re8
21. Qd3 (21. f4 gxf4 22. gxf4 Bf6 $11) 21... h5 22. f4 Bg7 23. Qxa6 h4 $132)
21. f4 ({Black probably kept the rook on c8 in order to meet} 21. Qd3 {with} c4
{but after} 22. Qf5 Rb8 {WHite may try using the b4-square with} 23. Na2 Bxb2
24. Nb4 $36) 21... gxf4 22. gxf4 Bf6 {Now, of course, the rook is useful on
the g-file.} 23. Rf3 Qd7 24. Re2 b5 25. axb5 axb5 26. Ne4 Bh4 27. f5 Ra8 $15 {
With initiative on both wings Antoshin, V (2440)-Beliavsky, A (2595) Frunze
1979 (½-½, 41)} *

