{[#] White has just played 11.Nd2. His plan is to develop a dangerous
initiative in the center by playing Nc4 followed by Bf3, Re1 and e4-e5. What
is Black's most flexible move in the position?} 1... Nb6 $1 {A very original
plan, which enjoyed some popularity lately. Black solves the conflict between
his minor pieces at the cost of weakening his queenside structure (see the
next move). From b6, the knight sustains ...c5-c4 leaving the diagonal and the
d7-square available for the bishop.} 2. a4 a5 {This is smaller concession than
it may seem. With his knights tied up to the defence of the central pawn,
White cannot establish a firm blockade on c4 and b5. Black can prepare ...Ng4
with ...h7-h5 (sometimes the knight jump could follow even after h2-h3 or else
play ...c5-c4.} *

